{"title_page": "Marta Petreu", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Marta Petreu\n| image                     = Marta Petreu.jpg\n| image_size                = 250px\n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Marta Petreu in February 2011\n| birth_name                = Rodica Cri\u015fan\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1955|3|14}}\n| birth_place               = [[Jucu]], Romania\n| occupation                = Philosopher, literary critic, essayist, poet\n}}\n'''Marta Petreu''' is the [[pen name]] of '''Rodica Marta Vartic''',  n\u00e9e Rodica Crisan (born 14 March 1955), a [[Romania]]n philosopher, literary critic, essayist and poet. A professor of Philosophy at the [[Babe\u015f-Bolyai University]] in [[Cluj-Napoca]], she has published eight books of essays and seven of poetry, and is the editor of the monthly magazine ''[[Apostrof]]''. Petreu is also noted as a historian of [[fascism]], which she notably dealt with in her book about the controversial stances of philosopher [[Emil Cioran]] (''An Infamous Past: E. M. Cioran and the Rise of Fascism in Romania'', 1999).\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|ro}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20040707131349/http://hiphi.ubbcluj.ro/fam/membri/mp/ Marta Petreu] at the [[Babe\u015f-Bolyai University]]\n* http://www.blouseroumaine.com/biographies/marta-petreu.html\n* http://www.agonia.net/index.php/author/0005366/Marta%20Petreu#bio\n{{commons category}}\n\n== Presence in English language anthologies ==\n\n* T''estament - 400 Years of Romanian Poetry - 400 de ani de poezie rom\u00e2neasc\u0103'' - bilingual edition - [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and principal translator) with [[Daniel Reynaud]], Adriana Paul & Eva Foster - Editura Minerva, 2019 - {{ISBN|978-973-21-1070-6}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petreu, Marta}}\n[[Category:Romanian essayists]]\n[[Category:Romanian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Romanian poets]]\n[[Category:Romanian women writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Babe\u0219-Bolyai University faculty]]\n[[Category:Historians of fascism]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Romanian women philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Romanian writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian literary critics]]\n[[Category:Romanian women poets]]\n[[Category:Romanian women essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:Women magazine editors]]\n\n\n{{Romania-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Marta Petreu\n| image                     = Marta Petreu.jpg\n| image_size                = 250px\n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Marta Petreu in February 2011\n| birth_name                = Rodica Cri\u015fan\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1955|3|14}}\n| birth_place               = [[Jucu]], Romania\n| occupation                = Philosopher, literary critic, essayist, poet\n}}\n'''Marta Petreu''' is the [[pen name]] of '''Rodica Marta Vartic''',  n\u00e9e Rodica Crisan (born 14 March 1955), a [[Romania]]n philosopher, literary critic, essayist and poet. A professor of Philosophy at the [[Babe\u015f-Bolyai University]] in [[Cluj-Napoca]], she has published eight books of essays and seven of poetry, and is the editor of the monthly magazine ''[[Apostrof]]''. Petreu is also noted as a historian of [[fascism]], which she notably dealt with in her book about the controversial stances of philosopher [[Emil Cioran]] (''An Infamous Past: E. M. Cioran and the Rise of Fascism in Romania'', 1999).\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|ro}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20040707131349/http://hiphi.ubbcluj.ro/fam/membri/mp/ Marta Petreu] at the [[Babe\u015f-Bolyai University]]\n* http://www.blouseroumaine.com/biographies/marta-petreu.html\n* http://www.agonia.net/index.php/author/0005366/Marta%20Petreu#bio\n{{commons category}}\n\n== Presence in English language anthologies ==\n\n* T''estament - 400 Years of Romanian Poetry - 400 de ani de poezie rom\u00e2neasc\u0103'' - bilingual edition - [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and principal translator) with [[Daniel Reynaud]], Adriana Paul & Eva Foster - Editura Minerva, 2019 - [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/978-973-21-1070-6|978-973-21-1070-6]]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petreu, Marta}}\n[[Category:Romanian essayists]]\n[[Category:Romanian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Romanian poets]]\n[[Category:Romanian women writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Babe\u0219-Bolyai University faculty]]\n[[Category:Historians of fascism]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Romanian women philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Romanian writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian literary critics]]\n[[Category:Romanian women poets]]\n[[Category:Romanian women essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:Women magazine editors]]\n\n\n{{Romania-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixISBN erroror other ISBN error usingAutoEd(or wrap invalid ISBN in template to show error message)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marta_Petreu"}
{"title_page": "Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization", "text_new": "[[Image:MALDITOF.jpg|thumb|right|200 px|MALDI TOF mass spectrometer]]\nIn [[mass spectrometry]], '''matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization''' ('''MALDI''') is an [[ionization]] technique that uses a laser energy absorbing  matrix to create [[ion]]s from large [[molecule]]s with minimal fragmentation.<ref name=\"HillenkampKaras1991\">{{cite journal|last1=Hillenkamp|first1=Franz|last2=Karas|first2=Michael|last3=Beavis|first3=Ronald C.|last4=Chait|first4=Brian T.|title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry of biopolymers|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=63|issue=24|year=1991|pages=1193A\u20131203A|issn=0003-2700|doi=10.1021/ac00024a002|pmid=1789447}}</ref> It has been applied to the analysis of [[biomolecule]]s ([[biopolymer]]s such as [[DNA]], [[protein]]s, [[peptide]]s and [[sugar]]s) and large [[organic chemistry|organic]] [[molecule]]s (such as [[polymer]]s, [[dendrimer]]s and other [[macromolecule]]s), which tend to be fragile and fragment when ionized by more conventional ionization methods. It is similar in character to [[electrospray ionization]] (ESI) in that both techniques are relatively soft (low fragmentation) ways of obtaining ions of large molecules in the gas phase, though MALDI typically produces far fewer multi-charged ions.\n\nMALDI methodology is a three-step process. First, the sample is mixed with a suitable matrix material and applied to a metal plate. Second, a pulsed [[laser]] irradiates the sample, triggering [[ablation]] and [[desorption]] of the sample and matrix material. Finally, the analyte molecules are ionized by being [[protonation|protonated]] or [[deprotonation|deprotonated]] in the hot plume of ablated gases, and then they can be accelerated into whichever mass spectrometer is used to analyse them.<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Karas|first1=Michael|last2=Kr\u00fcger|first2=Ralf|title=Ion Formation in MALDI: The Cluster Ionization Mechanism|journal=Chemical Reviews|volume=103|issue=2|year=2003|pages=427\u2013440|issn=0009-2665|doi=10.1021/cr010376a|pmid=12580637}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{main|History of mass spectrometry}}\n\nThe term matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI) was coined in 1985 by [[Franz Hillenkamp]], [[Michael Karas]] and their colleagues.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Bachmann |first2=D. |last3=Hillenkamp |first3=F. |year=1985 |title=Influence of the Wavelength in High-Irradiance Ultraviolet Laser Desorption Mass Spectrometry of Organic Molecules |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=57 |issue=14 |pages=2935\u20139 |doi=10.1021/ac00291a042 }}</ref> These researchers found that the [[amino acid]] [[alanine]] could be ionized more easily if it was mixed with the amino acid [[tryptophan]] and irradiated with a pulsed 266&nbsp;nm laser. The tryptophan was absorbing the laser energy and helping to ionize the non-absorbing alanine. Peptides up to the 2843 [[Dalton (unit)|Da]] peptide [[melittin]] could be ionized when mixed with this kind of \"matrix\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Bachmann |first2=D. |last3=Bahr |first3=U. |last4=Hillenkamp |first4=F. |year=1987 |title=Matrix-Assisted Ultraviolet Laser Desorption of Non-Volatile Compounds |journal=[[International Journal of Mass Spectrometry and Ion Processes]] |volume=78 |issue= |pages=53\u201368 |doi=10.1016/0168-1176(87)87041-6 |bibcode = 1987IJMSI..78...53K }}</ref> The breakthrough for large molecule laser desorption ionization came in 1987 when [[Koichi Tanaka]] of Shimadzu Corporation and his co-workers used what they called the \"ultra fine metal plus liquid matrix method\" that combined 30&nbsp;nm [[cobalt]] particles in [[glycerol]] with a 337&nbsp;nm [[nitrogen laser]] for ionization.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tanaka |first1=K. |last2=Waki |first2=H. |last3=Ido |first3=Y. |last4=Akita |first4=S. |last5=Yoshida |first5=Y. |last6=Yoshida |first6=T. |last7=Matsuo |first7=T. |year=1988 |title=Protein and Polymer Analyses up to ''m''/''z'' 100&nbsp;000 by Laser Ionization Time-of flight Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=2 |issue=20 |pages=151\u20133 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290020802 |bibcode=1988RCMS....2..151T }}</ref> Using this laser and matrix combination, Tanaka was able to ionize biomolecules as large as the 34,472 Da protein carboxypeptidase-A. Tanaka received one-quarter of the 2002 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] for demonstrating that, with the proper combination of laser wavelength and matrix, a protein can be ionized.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markides |first1=K. |last2=Gr\u00e4slund |first2=A. |date=9 October 2002 |title=Advanced information on the Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2002 |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/2002/advanced-chemistryprize2002.pdf |pages=1\u201313 |publisher=[[The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]] |accessdate=2013-08-28 }}</ref> Karas and Hillenkamp were subsequently able to ionize the 67 kDa protein albumin using a nicotinic acid matrix and a 266&nbsp;nm laser.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Hillenkamp |first2=F. |year=1988 |title=Laser desorption ionization of proteins with molecular masses exceeding 10,000 daltons |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=60 |issue=20 |pages=2299\u2013301 |doi=10.1021/ac00171a028 |pmid=3239801 }}</ref> Further improvements were realized through the use of a 355&nbsp;nm laser and the [[cinnamic acid]] derivatives [[ferulic acid]], [[caffeic acid]] and [[sinapinic acid]] as the matrix.<ref name=\"Beavis 1989\" /> The availability of small and relatively inexpensive [[nitrogen laser]]s operating at 337&nbsp;nm wavelength and the first commercial instruments introduced in the early 1990s brought MALDI to an increasing number of researchers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Bahr |first2=U. |year=1990 |title=Laser Desorption Ionization Mass Spectrometry of Large Biomolecules |journal=[[Trends in Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=9 |issue=10 |pages=321\u20135 |doi=10.1016/0165-9936(90)85065-F }}</ref> Today, mostly organic matrices are used for MALDI mass spectrometry.\n\n==Matrix ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style = \"float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:15px; width:40%\"\n|+ '''UV MALDI Matrix List'''\n! Compound !! Other Names !! Solvent !! Wavelength (nm) !! Applications\n|-\n! [[Gentisic acid|2,5-dihydroxy benzoic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Strupat |first=K. |last2=Karas |first2=M. |last3=Hillenkamp |first3=F. |year=1991 |title=2,5-Dihidroxybenzoic acid: A new matrix for laser desorption\u2014ionization mass spectrometry |journal=[[International Journal of Mass Spectrometry and Ion Processes]] |volume=72 |issue=111 |pages=89\u2013102 |bibcode=1991IJMSI.111...89S |doi=10.1016/0168-1176(91)85050-V }}</ref>\n| DHB, [[Gentisic acid]] || [[acetonitrile]], [[water]], [[methanol]], [[acetone]], [[chloroform]] || 337, 355, 266 || [[peptide]]s, [[nucleotide]]s, [[oligonucleotide]]s, [[oligosaccharide]]s\n|-\n! [[sinapinic acid|3,5-dimethoxy-4-hydroxycinnamic acid]]<ref name=\"Beavis 1989\">{{cite journal |last1=Beavis |first1=R. C. |last2=Chait |first2=B. T. |last3=Standing |first3=K. G. |year=1989 |title=Matrix-assisted laser-desorption mass spectrometry using 355&nbsp;nm radiation |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=436\u20139 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290031208 |pmid=2520224 |bibcode=1989RCMS....3..436B }}</ref><ref name=\"Beavis 1989a\">{{cite journal |last1=Beavis |first1=R. C. |last2=Chait |first2=B. T. |last3=Fales |first3=H. M. |year=1989 |title=Cinnamic acid derivatives as matrices for ultraviolet laser desorption mass spectrometry of proteins |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=432\u20135 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290031207 |pmid=2520223 |bibcode=1989RCMS....3..432B }}</ref>\n| sinapic acid; [[sinapinic acid]]; SA || [[acetonitrile]], water, acetone, chloroform || 337, 355, 266 || peptides, proteins, [[lipid]]s\n|-\n! [[ferulic acid|4-hydroxy-3-methoxycinnamic acid]]<ref name=\"Beavis 1989\" /><ref name=\"Beavis 1989a\" />\n| [[ferulic acid]]|| [[acetonitrile]], water, [[propanol]] || 337, 355, 266 || proteins \n|-\n! [[alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid|\u03b1-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Beavis |first1=R. C. |last2=Chaudhary |first2=T. |last3=Chait |first3=B. T. |year=1992 |title=\u03b1-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid as a matrix for matrix-assisted laser desorption mass spectrometry |journal=[[Organic Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=156\u20138 |doi=10.1002/oms.1210270217 }}</ref>\n| CHCA || [[acetonitrile]], water, [[ethanol]], acetone || 337, 355 ||peptides, lipids, nucleotides\n|-\n! [[Picolinic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tang |first1=K. |last2=Taranenko |first2=N. I. |last3=Allman |first3=S. L. |last4=Ch\u00e1ng |first4=L. Y. |last5=Chen |first5=C. H. |last6=Lubman |first6=D. M. |year=1994 |title=Detection of 500-nucleotide DNA by laser desorption mass spectrometry |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=8 |issue=9 |pages=727\u201330 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290080913 |pmid=7949335 |bibcode=1994RCMS....8..727T }}</ref>\n| PA || Ethanol || 266 || oligonucleotides\n|-\n! [[3-hydroxy picolinic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wu |first1=K. J. |last2=Steding |first2=A. |last3=Becker |first3=C. H. |year=1993 |title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption time-of-flight mass spectrometry of oligonucleotides using 3-hydroxypicolinic acid as an ultraviolet-sensitive matrix |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=142\u20136 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290070206 |pmid=8457722 |bibcode=1993RCMS....7..142W }}</ref>\n|| HPA|| Ethanol || 337, 355 || oligonucleotides\n|}\n\nThe [[matrix (mass spectrometry)|matrix]] consists of [[crystal]]lized molecules, of which the three most commonly used are 3,5-dimethoxy-4-hydroxycinnamic [[acid]] ([[sinapinic acid]]), [[alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid|\u03b1-cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid]] (\u03b1-CHCA, alpha-cyano or alpha-matrix) and [[2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid]] (DHB).<ref>{{Cite book|title = Using Mass Spectrometry for Drug Metabolism Studies|last = Korfmacher|first = Walter A.|publisher = CRC Press|year = 2009|isbn = 9781420092219|location = |page = 342|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=C0nzGNCHhL8C&pg=PA342}}</ref> A [[solution]] of one of these molecules is made, often in a mixture of highly purified [[water]] and an organic [[solvent]] such as [[acetonitrile]] (ACN) or [[ethanol]]. A counter ion source such as [[Trifluoroacetic acid]] (TFA) is usually added to generate the [M+H] ions. A good example of a matrix-solution would be 20 [[Milligram per liter|mg/mL]] sinapinic acid in ACN:water:TFA (50:50:0.1).\n\n[[Image:Cinnamic acid substitutions.PNG|left|thumb|250 px|Notation for cinnamic acid substitutions.]]\nThe identification of suitable matrix compounds is determined to some extent by trial and error, but they are based on some specific molecular design considerations. They are of a fairly low molecular weight (to allow easy vaporization), but are large enough (with a low enough vapor pressure) not to evaporate during sample preparation or while standing in the mass spectrometer. They are often acidic, therefore act as a proton source to encourage ionization of the analyte. Basic matrices have also been reported.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Fitzgerald |first1=M. C. |last2=Parr |first2=G. R. |last3=Smith |first3=L. M. |year=1993 |title=Basic matrixes for the matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry of proteins and oligonucleotides |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=65 |issue=22 |pages=3204\u201311 |doi=10.1021/ac00070a007 |pmid=8291672 }}</ref> They have a strong optical absorption in either the UV or IR range,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Zenobi |first1=R. |last2=Knochenmuss |first2=R. |year=1998 |title=Ion formation in MALDI mass spectrometry |journal=[[Mass Spectrometry Reviews]] |volume=17 |pages=337\u2013366 |issue=5 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2787(1998)17:5<337::AID-MAS2>3.0.CO;2-S |bibcode=1998MSRv...17..337Z }}</ref> so that they rapidly and efficiently absorb the laser irradiation. This efficiency is commonly associated with chemical structures incorporating several [[conjugated double bond]]s, as seen in the structure of [[cinnamic acid]]. They are functionalized with polar groups, allowing their use in aqueous solutions. They typically contain a chromophore.\n\nThe matrix solution is mixed with the analyte (e.g. [[protein]]-sample). A mixture of water and organic solvent allows both [[hydrophobic]] and water-soluble ([[hydrophilic]]) molecules to dissolve into the solution. This solution is spotted onto a MALDI plate (usually a metal plate designed for this purpose). The solvents vaporize, leaving only the recrystallized matrix, but now with analyte molecules embedded into MALDI crystals. The matrix and the analyte are said to be co-crystallized. Co-crystallization is a key issue in selecting a proper matrix to obtain a good quality mass spectrum of the analyte of interest.\n\nIn analysis of biological systems, Inorganic salts, which are also part of protein extracts, interfere with the ionization process. The salts can be removed by solid phase extraction or by washing the dried-droplet MALDI spots with cold water.<ref name=\"XuBruening2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=Yingda|last2=Bruening|first2=Merlin L.|last3=Watson|first3=J. Throck|title=Non-specific, on-probe cleanup methods for MALDI-MS samples|journal=Mass Spectrometry Reviews|volume=22|issue=6|year=2003|pages=429\u2013440|issn=0277-7037|doi=10.1002/mas.10064|pmid=14528495|bibcode=2003MSRv...22..429X}}</ref> Both methods can also remove other substances from the sample. The matrix-protein mixture is not homogenous because the polarity difference leads to a separation of the two substances during co-crystallization. The spot diameter of the target is much larger than that of the laser, which makes it necessary to make many laser shots at different places of the target, to get the statistical average of the substance concentration within the target spot.\n\n[[File:Naphthalene.png|thumbnail|right|Naphthalene and naphthalene-like compounds can also be used as a matrix to ionize a sample]]\nThe matrix can be used to tune the instrument to ionize the sample in different ways. As mentioned above, acid-base like reactions are often utilized to ionize the sample, however, molecules with conjugated pi systems, such as naphthalene like compounds, can also serve as an electron acceptor and thus a matrix for MALDI/TOF.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nazim Boutaghou | first1 = M. | last2 = Cole | first2 = R. B. | year = 2012 | title = 9,10-Diphenylanthracene as a matrix for MALDI-MS electron transfer secondary reactions | url = | journal = J. Mass Spectrom | volume = 47 | issue = | pages = 995\u20131003 | doi = 10.1002/jms.3027 }}</ref> This is particularly useful in studying molecules that also possess [[Conjugated system|conjugated pi systems]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Suzuki | first1 = T. | last2 = Midonoya | first2 = H. | last3 = Shioi | first3 = Y. | year = 2009 | title = Analysis of chlorophylls and their derivatives by matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization\u2013time-of-flight mass spectrometry | url = | journal = Anal. Biochem | volume = 390 | issue = | pages = 57\u201362 | doi = 10.1016/j.ab.2009.04.005 }}</ref> The most widely used application for these matrices is studying porphyrin like compounds such as [[chlorophyll]]. These matrices have been shown to have better ionization patterns that do not result in odd fragmentation patterns or complete loss of side chains.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wei | first1 = J. | last2 = Li | first2 = H. | last3 = Barrow | first3 = M. P. | last4 = O'Connor | first4 = P. B. | year = 2013 | title = Structural characterization of chlorophyll-a by high resolution tandem mass spectrometry | url = | journal = J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom | volume = 24 | issue = | pages = 753\u2013760 }}</ref> It has also been suggested that conjugated porphryin like molecules can serve as a matrix and cleave themselves eliminating the need for a separate matrix compound.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Srinivasan | first1 = N. | last2 = Haney | first2 = C. A. | last3 = Lindsey | first3 = J. S. | last4 = Zhang | first4 = W. | last5 = Chait | first5 = B. T. | year = 1999 | title = Investigation of MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry of diverse synthetic metalloporphyrins, phthalocyanines and multiporphyrin arrays | url = | journal = J. Porphyrins Phthalocyanines | volume = 3 | issue = | pages = 283\u2013291 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1099-1409(199904)3:4<283::AID-JPP132>3.0.CO;2-F }}</ref>\n\n==Instrumentation==\n[[File:MALDI TOF EN.png|thumb|Diagram of a MALDI TOF instrument. Sample matrix ionized by radiant energy is ejected from surface. Sample travels into mass analyzer and is substantially detected.]]\nThere are several variations of the MALDI technology and comparable instruments are today produced for very different purposes. From more academic and analytical, to more industrial and high throughput. The MS field has expanded into requiring ultrahigh resolution mass spectrometry such as the FT-ICR instruments<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biocompare.com/Editorial-Articles/41589-Talking-About-a-Revolution-FT-ICR-Mass-Spectrometry-Offers-High-Resolution-and-Mass-Accuracy-for-Pr/|title=Talking About a Revolution: FT-ICR Mass Spectrometry Offers High Resolution and Mass Accuracy for Pr}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 2129108 | pages=1309\u20131310 | volume=389 | issue=5 | journal=Anal Bioanal Chem | title=Ultrahigh resolution mass spectrometry | doi=10.1007/s00216-007-1589-0| year=2007 | last1=Schmitt-Kopplin | first1=P | last2=Hertkorn | first2=N }}</ref> as well as more high-throughput instruments.<ref>{{cite journal |journal= Journal of Microbiological Methods |volume= 86|issue= 3|date= September 2011| pages= 327\u2013336|doi=10.1016/j.mimet.2011.06.004|pmid = 21699925|title=Evaluation of MALDI-TOF MS as a tool for high-throughput dereplication|last1= Ghyselinck |first1= Jonas |last2= Van Hoorde |first2= Koenraad |last3= Hoste |first3= Bart |last4= Heylen |first4= Kim |last5= De Vos |first5= Paul }}</ref> As many MALDI MS instruments can be bought with an interchangeable ionization source ([[Electrospray ionization]], MALDI, [[Atmospheric pressure ionization]], etc.) the technologies often overlap and many times any soft ionization method could potentially be used. For more variations of soft ionization methods go to [[Soft laser desorption]] or [[Ion source]].\n\n===Laser===\nMALDI techniques typically employ the use of UV [[lasers]] such as nitrogen lasers (337&nbsp;nm) and frequency-tripled and quadrupled [[Nd:YAG lasers]] (355&nbsp;nm and 266&nbsp;nm respectively).<ref name=\"Dreisewerd2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Dreisewerd|first1=Klaus|title=Recent methodological advances in MALDI mass spectrometry|journal=Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry|volume=406|issue=9\u201310|year=2014|pages=2261\u20132278|issn=1618-2642|doi=10.1007/s00216-014-7646-6|pmid=24652146}}</ref>\n\nInfrared laser wavelengths used for infrared MALDI include the 2.94&nbsp;\u03bcm [[Er:YAG laser]], mid-IR [[optical parametric oscillator]], and 10.6&nbsp;\u03bcm [[carbon dioxide laser]]. Although not as common, infrared lasers are used due to their softer mode of ionization.<ref>{{cite book |last=Murray |first1=K |chapter-url=https://www.elsevier.com/books/the-encyclopedia-of-mass-spectrometry/gross/978-0-08-043801-6 |title=The Encyclopedia of Mass Spectrometry |chapter=Chapter 9 Desorption by Photons: Laser Desorption and Matridx-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization (MALDI) \u2013 Infrared Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization |volume=Volume 6: Ionization Methods |editor-last=Gross |editor-first=Michael L. |editor2-last=Caprioli |editor2-first=Richard M. |work= |publisher=Elsevier Science |year=2006 |isbn=9780080438016 |accessdate=2017-04-05 }}</ref> IR-MALDI also has the advantage of greater material removal (useful for biological samples), less low-mass interferences, and compatibility with other matrix-free laser desorption mass spectrometry methods.\n\n=== Time of flight ===\n[[Image:MALDI Target.jpg|thumb|right|300 px|Sample target for a MALDI mass spectrometer]]\nThe type of a mass spectrometer most widely used with MALDI is the [[Time-of-flight mass spectrometry|TOF]] (time-of-flight mass spectrometer), mainly due to its large mass range. The TOF measurement procedure is also ideally suited to the MALDI ionization process since the pulsed laser takes individual 'shots' rather than working in continuous operation. MALDI-TOF instruments are often equipped with a [[reflectron]] (an \"ion mirror\")  that reflects ions using an electric field. This increases the ion flight path, thereby increasing time of flight between ions of different m/z and increasing resolution. Modern commercial [[reflectron]] TOF instruments reach a resolving power m/\u0394m of 50,000 FWHM (full-width half-maximum, \u0394m defined as the peak width at 50% of peak height) or more.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xian|first=Feng|last2=Hendrickson|first2=Christopher L.|last3=Marshall|first3=Alan G.|date=2012-01-17|title=High Resolution Mass Spectrometry|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=84|issue=2|pages=708\u2013719|doi=10.1021/ac203191t|pmid=22263633|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>\n\nMALDI has been coupled with [[Ion-mobility spectrometry\u2013mass spectrometry|IMS]]-TOF MS to identify phosphorylated and non-phosphorylated peptides.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ruotolo |first1=B. T. |last2=Gillig |first2=K. J. |last3=Woods |first3=A. S. |last4=Egan |first4=T. F. |last5=Ugarov |first5=M. V. |last6=Schultz |first6=J. A. |last7=Russell |first7=D. H. |year=2004 |title=Analysis of Phosphorylated Peptides by Ion Mobility-Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=76 |issue=22 |pages=6727\u20136733 |doi=10.1021/ac0498009 |pmid=15538797 }}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ruotolo |first1=B. T. |last2=Verbeck |first2=G. F. |last3=Thomson |first3=L. M. |last4=Woods |first4=A. S. |last5=Gillig |first5=K. J. |last6=Russell |first6=D. H. |year=2002 |title=Distinguishing between Phosphorylated and Nonphosphorylated Peptides with Ion Mobility\u2212Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Journal of Proteome Research]] |volume=1 |issue=4|pages=303\u2013306 |doi=10.1021/pr025516r }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nMALDI-[[FT-ICR]] MS has been demonstrated to be a useful technique where high resolution MALDI-MS measurements are desired.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pasa-Tolic |first1=L. |last2=Huang |first2=Y. |last3=Guan |first3=S. |last4=Kim |first4=H. S. |last5=Marshall |first5=A. G. |year=1995 |title=Ultrahigh-resolution matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectra of peptides |journal=[[Journal of Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=30 |issue=6 |pages=825\u2013833 |doi=10.1002/jms.1190300607 |bibcode=1995JMSp...30..825P }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n=== Atmospheric pressure ===\nAtmospheric pressure (AP) matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI) is an ionization technique (ion source) that in contrast to vacuum MALDI operates at normal atmospheric environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Laiko |first1=V. V. |last2=Baldwin |first2=M. A. |last3=Burlingame |first3=A. L. |year=2000 |title=Atmospheric pressure matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=72 |issue=4 |pages=652\u20137 |pmid=10701247 |doi=10.1021/ac990998k }}</ref> The main difference between vacuum MALDI and AP-MALDI is the pressure in which the ions are created. In vacuum MALDI, ions are typically produced at 10 mTorr or less while in AP-MALDI ions are formed in [[atmospheric pressure]]. In the past the main disadvantage of AP MALDI technique compared to the conventional vacuum MALDI has been its limited sensitivity; however, ions can be transferred into the mass spectrometer with high efficiency and attomole detection limits have been reported.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strupat |first1=K. |last2=Scheibner |first2=O. |last3=Arrey |first3=T. |last4=Bromirski |first4=M. |year=2011 |title=Biological Applications of AP MALDI with Thermo Scientific Exactive Orbitrap MS |url=http://www.apmaldi.com/images/stories/005-111101-an30224-maldi-generalapp_6s_v4a_kp.pdf |work=443-539-1710 |publisher=[[Thermo Scientific]] |accessdate=17 June 2011 }}</ref> AP-MALDI is used in mass spectrometry (MS) in a variety of applications ranging from proteomics to drug discovery. Popular topics that are addressed by AP-MALDI mass spectrometry include: proteomics; mass analysis of DNA, RNA, PNA, lipids, oligosaccharides, phosphopeptides, bacteria, small molecules and synthetic polymers, similar applications as available also for vacuum MALDI instruments. The AP-MALDI ion source is easily coupled to an ion trap mass spectrometer<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Laiko |first1=V. V. |last2=Moyer |first2=S. C. |last3=Cotter |first3=R. J. |year=2000 |title=Atmospheric pressure MALDI/ion trap mass spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=72 |issue=21 |pages=5239\u201343 |doi=10.1021/ac000530d |pmid=11080870 }}</ref> or any other MS system equipped with [[Electrospray ionization|ESI]] (electrospray ionization) or nanoESI source.\n\n===Aerosol===\nIn [[aerosol mass spectrometry]], one of the ionization techniques consists in firing a laser to individual droplets. These systems are called [[Aerosol mass spectrometry#Single-particle measurements|single particle mass spectrometers (SPMS)]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Yong Jie |last2=Sun |first2=Yele |last3=Zhang |first3=Qi |last4=Li |first4=Xue |last5=Li |first5=Mei |last6=Zhou |first6=Zhen |last7=Chan |first7=Chak K. |title=Real-time chemical characterization of atmospheric particulate matter in China: A review |journal=Atmospheric Environment |date=June 2017 |volume=158 |pages=270\u2013304 |doi=10.1016/j.atmosenv.2017.02.027|bibcode=2017AtmEn.158..270L }}</ref> The sample may optionally be mixed with a MALDI matrix prior to aerosolization.\n\n==Ionization mechanism==\nThe [[laser]] is fired at the matrix crystals in the dried-droplet spot. The matrix absorbs the laser energy and it is thought that primarily the matrix is desorbed and ionized (by addition of a [[proton]]) by this event. The hot plume produced during ablation contains many species: neutral and ionized matrix molecules, protonated and deprotonated matrix molecules, matrix clusters and [[Droplet|nanodroplets]]. Ablated species may participate in the ionization of analyte, though the mechanism of MALDI is still debated. The matrix is then thought to transfer protons to the analyte molecules (e.g., protein molecules), thus charging the analyte.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Knochenmuss |first=R |year=2006 |title=Ion formation mechanisms in UV-MALDI |journal=[[Analyst (journal)|Analyst]] |volume=131 |issue=9 |pages=966\u2013986 |bibcode=2006Ana...131..966K |doi=10.1039/b605646f |pmid=17047796 }}</ref> An ion observed after this process will consist of the initial neutral molecule [M] with ions added or removed. This is called a quasimolecular ion, for example [M+H]<sup>+</sup> in the case of an added proton, [M+Na]<sup>+</sup> in the case of an added [[sodium]] ion, or [M-H]<sup>\u2212</sup> in the case of a removed proton. MALDI is capable of creating singly charged ions or multiply charged ions ([M+nH]<sup>n+</sup>) depending on the nature of the matrix, the laser intensity, and/or the voltage used. Note that these are all even-electron species. Ion signals of radical cations (photoionized molecules) can be observed, e.g., in the case of matrix molecules and other organic molecules.\n\nThe gas phase proton transfer model,<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\" /> implemented as the coupled physical and chemical dynamics (CPCD) model,<ref name=\"Knochenmuss2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Knochenmuss|first1=Richard|title=The Coupled Chemical and Physical Dynamics Model of MALDI|journal=Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry|volume=9|issue=1|year=2016|pages=365\u2013385|issn=1936-1327|doi=10.1146/annurev-anchem-071015-041750|pmid=27070182|bibcode=2016ARAC....9..365K}}</ref> of UV laser MALDI postulates primary and secondary processes leading to ionization.<ref name=\"Knochenmuss2006\">{{cite journal|last1=Knochenmuss|first1=Richard|title=Ion formation mechanisms in UV-MALDI|journal=The Analyst|volume=131|issue=9|year=2006|pages=966\u201386|issn=0003-2654|doi=10.1039/b605646f|pmid=17047796|bibcode=2006Ana...131..966K}}</ref> Primary processes involve initial charge separation through absorption of photons by the matrix and pooling of the energy to form matrix ion pairs. Primary ion formation occurs through absorption of a UV photon to create excited state molecules by\n\n:S<sub>0</sub> + h\u03bd \u2192 S<sub>1</sub>\n\n:S<sub>1</sub> + S<sub>1</sub> \u2192 S<sub>0</sub> + S<sub>n</sub>\n\n:S<sub>1</sub> + S<sub>n</sub> \u2192 M<sup>+</sup> + M<sup>\u2212</sup>\n\nwhere S<sub>0</sub> is the ground electronic state, S<sub>1</sub> the first electronic excited state, and S<sub>n</sub> is a higher electronic excited state.<ref name=\"Knochenmuss2016\" /> The product ions can be proton transfer or electron transfer ion pairs, indicated by M<sup>+</sup> and M<sup>\u2212</sup> above. Secondary processes involve ion-molecule reactions to form analyze ions.\n\n[[File:LuckySurvivor.jpg|thumb|right|300 px|In the lucky survivor model, positive ions can be formed from highly charged clusters produced during break-up of the matrix- and analyte-containing solid.]]\nThe lucky survivor model (cluster ionization mechanism<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\" />) postulates that analyte molecules are incorporated in the matrix maintaining the charge state from solution.<ref name=\"KarasGl\u00fcckmann2000\">{{cite journal|last1=Karas|first1=Michael|last2=Gl\u00fcckmann|first2=Matthias|last3=Sch\u00e4fer|first3=J\u00fcrgen|title=Ionization in matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization: singly charged molecular ions are the lucky survivors|journal=Journal of Mass Spectrometry|volume=35|issue=1|year=2000|pages=1\u201312|issn=1076-5174|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1096-9888(200001)35:1<1::AID-JMS904>3.0.CO;2-0|pmid=10633229|bibcode=2000JMSp...35....1K}}</ref><ref name=\"McEwenLarsen2015\">{{cite journal|last1=McEwen|first1=Charles N.|last2=Larsen|first2=Barbara S.|title=Fifty years of desorption ionization of nonvolatile compounds|journal=International Journal of Mass Spectrometry|volume=377|year=2015|pages=515\u2013531|issn=1387-3806|doi=10.1016/j.ijms.2014.07.018|bibcode=2015IJMSp.377..515M}}</ref> Ion formation occurs through charge separation upon fragmentation of laser ablated clusters.<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\"/> Ions that are not neutralized by recombination with [[photoelectron]]s or [[counter ion]]s are the so-called lucky survivors.\n\nThe thermal model postulates that the high temperature facilitates the proton transfer between matrix and analyte in melted matrix liquid.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Ionization Mechanism of Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization|journal=Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry|volume=8|pages=21\u201339|last=Lu|first=I.-Chung|last2=Lee|first2=Chuping|date=2015|language=|doi=10.1146/annurev-anchem-071114-040315|pmid=26132345|last3=Lee|first3=Yuan-Tseh|last4=Ni|first4=Chi-Kung|bibcode=2015ARAC....8...21L}}</ref> Ion-to-neutral ratio is an important parameter to justify the theoretical model, and the mistaken citation of ion-to-neutral ratio could result in an erroneous determination of the ionization mechanism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tsai|first=Ming-Tsang|last2=Lee|first2=Sheng|last3=Lu|first3=I-Chung|last4=Chu|first4=Kuan Yu|last5=Liang|first5=Chi-Wei|last6=Lee|first6=Chih Hao|last7=Lee|first7=Yuan T.|last8=Ni|first8=Chi-Kung|date=2013-05-15|title=Ion-to-neutral ratio of 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid in matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization|journal=Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry|language=en|volume=27|issue=9|pages=955\u2013963|doi=10.1002/rcm.6534|pmid=23592197|issn=1097-0231|bibcode=2013RCMS...27..955T}}</ref> The model quantitatively predicts the increase in total ion intensity as a function of the concentration and proton affinity of the analytes, and the ion-to-neutral ratio as a function of the laser fluences.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=I-Chung|last2=Lee|first2=Chuping|last3=Chen|first3=Hui-Yuan|last4=Lin|first4=Hou-Yu|last5=Hung|first5=Sheng-Wei|last6=Dyakov|first6=Yuri A.|last7=Hsu|first7=Kuo-Tung|last8=Liao|first8=Chih-Yu|last9=Lee|first9=Yin-Yu|date=2014|title=Ion Intensity and Thermal Proton Transfer in Ultraviolet Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|volume=118|issue=15|pages=4132\u20134139|doi=10.1021/jp5008076|pmid=24707818|issn=1520-6106}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=I.-Chung|last2=Chu|first2=Kuan Yu|last3=Lin|first3=Chih-Yuan|last4=Wu|first4=Shang-Yun|last5=Dyakov|first5=Yuri A.|last6=Chen|first6=Jien-Lian|last7=Gray-Weale|first7=Angus|last8=Lee|first8=Yuan-Tseh|last9=Ni|first9=Chi-Kung|date=2015|title=Ion-to-Neutral Ratios and Thermal Proton Transfer in Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|language=en|volume=26|issue=7|pages=1242\u20131251|doi=10.1007/s13361-015-1112-3|pmid=25851654|issn=1044-0305|bibcode=2015JASMS..26.1242L}}</ref> This model also suggests that metal ion adducts (e.g., [M+Na]<sup>+</sup> or [M+K]<sup>+</sup>) are mainly generated from the thermally induced dissolution of salt.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Chuping|last2=Lu|first2=I.-Chung|last3=Hsu|first3=Hsu Chen|last4=Lin|first4=Hou-Yu|last5=Liang|first5=Sheng-Ping|last6=Lee|first6=Yuan-Tseh|last7=Ni|first7=Chi-Kung|date=2016|title=Formation of Metal-Related Ions in Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|language=en|volume=27|issue=9|pages=1491\u20131498|doi=10.1007/s13361-016-1424-y|pmid=27306427|issn=1044-0305|bibcode=2016JASMS..27.1491L}}</ref>\n\nThe [[matrix-assisted ionization]] (MAI) method uses matrix preparation similar to MALDI but does not require laser ablation to produce analyte ions of volatile or nonvolatile compounds.<ref name=\"Trimpin2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Trimpin|first1=Sarah|title=\"Magic\" Ionization Mass Spectrometry|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|volume=27|issue=1|year=2015|pages=4\u201321|issn=1044-0305|doi=10.1007/s13361-015-1253-4|pmid=26486514|pmc=4686549|bibcode=2016JASMS..27....4T}}</ref>  Simply exposing the matrix with analyte to the vacuum of the mass spectrometer creates ions with nearly identical charge states to electrospray ionization.<ref name=\"Trimpin\">{{cite journal |author=Trimpin, S, Inutan, ED |title=Matrix Assisted Ionization in Vacuum, a Sensitive and Widely Applicable Ionization Method for Mass Spectrometry |journal=J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom.|volume=24 |issue=5 |pages=722\u2013732 |doi=10.1007/s13361-012-0571-z|pmid=23526166 |year=2013 |bibcode=2013JASMS..24..722T }}</ref> It is suggested that there are likely mechanistic commonality between this process and MALDI.<ref name=\"McEwenLarsen2015\" />\n\n== Applications ==\n\n=== Biochemistry ===\nIn [[proteomics]], MALDI is used for the rapid identification of proteins isolated by using [[gel electrophoresis]]: [[SDS-PAGE]], [[size exclusion chromatography]], affinity chromatography, strong/weak ion exchange, isotope coded protein labelling (ICPL), and [[two-dimensional gel electrophoresis]]. [[Peptide mass fingerprinting]] is the most popular analytical application of MALDI-TOF mass spectrometers. MALDI TOF/TOF mass spectrometers are used to reveal amino acid sequence of peptides using post-source decay or high energy [[collision-induced dissociation]] (further use see [[mass spectrometry]]).\n\nLoss of sialic acid has been identified in papers when DHB has been used as a matrix for MALDI MS analysis of glycosylated peptides. Using sinapinic acid, 4-HCCA and DHB as matrices, S. Martin studied loss of sialic acid in glycosylated peptides by metastable decay in MALDI/TOF in linear mode and reflector mode.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Huberty |first1=M. C. |last2=Vath |first2=J. E. |last3=Yu |first3=W. |last4=Martin |first4=S. A. |year=1993 |title=Site-specific carbohydrate identification in recombinant proteins using MALD-TOF MS |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=65 |issue=20 |pages=2791\u20132800 |doi=10.1021/ac00068a015 |pmid=8250262 }}</ref> A group at Shimadzu Corporation derivatized the sialic acid by an amidation reaction as a way to improve detection sensitivity<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sekiya |first1=S. |last2=Wada |first2=Y. |last3=Tanaka |first3=K. |year=2005 |title=Derivatization for Stabilizing Sialic Acids in MALDI-MS |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=77 |issue=15 |pages=4962\u20134968 |doi=10.1021/ac050287o |pmid=16053310 }}</ref> and also demonstrated that ionic liquid matrix reduces a loss of sialic acid during MALDI/TOF MS analysis of sialylated oligosaccharides.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fukuyama |first1=Y. |last2=Nakaya |first2=S. |last3=Yamazaki |first3=Y. |last4=Tanaka |first4=K. |year=2008 |title=Ionic Liquid Matrixes Optimized for MALDI-MS of Sulfated/Sialylated/Neutral Oligosaccharides and Glycopeptides |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=80 |issue=6 |pages=2171\u20132179 |doi=10.1021/ac7021986 |pmid=18275166 }}</ref> THAP,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Papac |first1=D. I. |last2=Wong |first2=A. |last3=Jones |first3=A. J. S. |year=1996 |title=Analysis of Acidic Oligosaccharides and Glycopeptides by Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=68 |issue=18 |pages=3215\u20133223 |doi=10.1021/ac960324z |pmid=8797382 }}</ref> DHAP,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Harvey |first1=D. J. |year=1999 |title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry of carbohydrates |journal=[[Mass Spectrometry Reviews]] |volume=18 |issue=6 |pages=349\u2013451 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2787(1999)18:6<349::AID-MAS1>3.0.CO;2-H |bibcode=1999MSRv...18..349H |citeseerx=10.1.1.1012.1931 }}</ref> and a mixture of 2-aza-2-thiothymine and phenylhydrazine<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lattova |first1=E. |last2=Chen |first2=V. C. |last3=Varma |first3=S. |last4=Bezabeh |first4=T. |last5=Perreault |first5=H. |year=2007 |title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization on-target method for the investigation of oligosaccharides and glycosylation sites in glycopeptides and glycoproteins |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=21 |issue=10 |pages=1644\u20131650 |doi=10.1002/rcm.3007 |pmid=17465012 |bibcode=2007RCMS...21.1644L }}</ref> have been identified as matrices that could be used to minimize loss of sialic acid during MALDI MS analysis of glycosylated peptides.\n\nIt has been reported that a reduction in loss of some post-translational modifications can be accomplished if IR MALDI is used instead of UV MALDI<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tajiri |first1=M. |last2=Takeuchi |first2=T. |last3=Wada |first3=Y. |year=2009 |title=Distinct Features of Matrix-Assisted 6&nbsp;\u03bcm Infrared Laser Desorption/Ionization Mass Spectrometry in Biomolecular Analysis |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=81 |issue=16 |pages=6750\u20136755 |doi=10.1021/ac900695q |pmid=19627133 }}</ref>\n\nIn molecular biology, a mixture of [[5-methoxysalicylic acid]] and [[spermine]] can be used as a matrix for [[oligonucleotide]]s analysis in MALDI mass spectrometry,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Distler |first1=A. M. |last2=Allison |first2=J. |year=2001 |title=5-Methoxysalicylic acid and spermine: A new matrix for the matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry analysis of oligonucleotides |journal=[[Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=456\u201362 |doi=10.1016/S1044-0305(01)00212-4 |pmid=11322192 }}</ref> for instance after [[oligonucleotide synthesis]].\n\n===Organic chemistry===\nSome synthetic macromolecules, such as [[catenane]]s and [[rotaxane]]s, [[dendrimer]]s and [[hyperbranched polymer]]s, and other assemblies, have molecular weights extending into the thousands or tens of thousands, where most ionization techniques have difficulty producing molecular ions. MALDI is a simple and fast analytical method that can allow chemists to rapidly analyze the results of such syntheses and verify their results.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n===Polymers===\nIn polymer chemistry MALDI can be used to determine the [[molar mass distribution]].<ref name=\"isbn3-540-44259-6\">{{cite book |last1=Schrepp |first1=W. |last2=Pasch |first2=H. |year=2003 |title=MALDI-TOF Mass Spectrometry of Synthetic Polymers |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |isbn=978-3-540-44259-2 }}</ref> Polymers with [[polydispersity]] greater than 1.2 are difficult to characterize with MALDI due to the signal intensity discrimination against higher mass oligomers.<ref name=Nielen1997>{{Cite journal |last1=Nielen |first1=M. W. F. |last2=Malucha |first2=S. |year=1997 |title=Characterization of polydisperse synthetic polymers by size-exclusion chromatography/matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=1194\u20131204 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-0231(199707)11:11<1194::AID-RCM935>3.0.CO;2-L |bibcode=1997RCMS...11.1194N }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9666717\">{{cite journal |last1=Wu |first1=K. J. |last2=Odom |first2=R. W. |year=1998 |title=Characterizing synthetic polymers by MALDI MS |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=70 |issue=13 |pages=456A\u2013461A |pmid=9666717 |doi=10.1021/ac981910q }}</ref><ref name=Schriemer1997>{{Cite journal |last1=Schriemer |first1=D. C. |last2=Li |first2=L. |year=1997 |title=Mass Discrimination in the Analysis of Polydisperse Polymers by MALDI Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry. 2. Instrumental Issues |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=69 |issue=20 |pages=4176\u20134183 |doi=10.1021/ac9707794 }}</ref>\n\nA good matrix for polymers is [[dithranol]]<ref name=\"SchaibergerMoss2008\">{{cite journal|last1=Schaiberger|first1=Audrey M.|last2=Moss|first2=Jason A.|title=Optimized sample preparation for MALDI mass spectrometry analysis of protected synthetic peptides|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|volume=19|issue=4|year=2008|pages=614\u2013619|issn=1044-0305|doi=10.1016/j.jasms.2008.01.010|pmid=18295503}}</ref> or [[silver trifluoroacetate|AgTFA]].<ref name=\"BahrDeppe1992\">{{cite journal|last1=Bahr|first1=Ute.|last2=Deppe|first2=Andreas.|last3=Karas|first3=Michael.|last4=Hillenkamp|first4=Franz.|last5=Giessmann|first5=Ulrich.|title=Mass spectrometry of synthetic polymers by UV-matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=64|issue=22|year=1992|pages=2866\u20132869|issn=0003-2700|doi=10.1021/ac00046a036}}</ref> The sample must first be mixed with dithranol and the AgTFA added afterwards; otherwise the sample would precipitate out of solution.\n\n===Microbiology===\nMALDI/TOF spectra are used for the identification of micro-organisms such as bacteria or fungi. A portion of a colony of the microbe in question is placed onto the sample target and overlaid with matrix. The mass spectra generated are analyzed by dedicated software and compared with stored profiles. Species diagnosis by this procedure is much faster, more accurate and cheaper than other procedures based on immunological or biochemical tests. MALDI/TOF is becoming a standard method for species identification in medical microbiological laboratories.<ref name=\"pmid19583519\">{{cite journal |last1=Seng |first1=P. |last2=Drancourt |first2=M. |last3=Gouriet |first3=F. |last4=La Scola |first4=B. |last5=Fournier |first5=P. E. |last6=Rolain |first6=J. M. |last7=Raoult |first7=D. |title=Ongoing revolution in bacteriology: routine identification of bacteria by matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry |journal=[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=552\u20133 |year=2009 |pmid=19583519 |doi=10.1086/600885 }}</ref><ref name=\"SandrinGoldstein2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Sandrin|first1=Todd R.|last2=Goldstein|first2=Jason E.|last3=Schumaker|first3=Stephanie|title=MALDI TOF MS profiling of bacteria at the strain level: A review|journal=Mass Spectrometry Reviews|volume=32|issue=3|year=2013|pages=188\u2013217|issn=0277-7037|doi=10.1002/mas.21359|pmid=22996584|bibcode=2013MSRv...32..188S}}</ref>\n\nOne main advantage over other microbiological identification methods is its ability to rapidly and reliably identify, at low cost, a wide variety of microorganisms directly from the selective medium used to isolate them. The absence of the need to purify the suspect or \"presumptive\" colony<ref>{{Cite book|title = Molecular Microbial Diagnostic Methods - Pathways to Implementation for the Food and Water Industries|last = Capocefalo M., Ridley E. V., Tranfield E. Y. & Thompson K. C.|publisher = Elsevier|year = 2015|isbn = 978-0-12-416999-9|location = |pages = |chapter = Ch. 9 - MALDI-TOF: A rapid microbiological confirmation technique for food and water analysis|editor1=Cook N. |editor2=D'Agostino M. |editor3=Thompson K. C. }}</ref> allows for a much faster turn-around times.\n\nAnother advantage is the potential to predict [[antibiotic susceptibility]] of bacteria. A single mass spectral peak can predict methicillin resistance of ''Staphylococcus aureus'' <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rhoads | first1 = DD | year = 2016 | title = The presence of a single MALDI-TOF mass spectral peak predicts methicillin resistance in staphylococci. ''et al.'' | url = | journal = Diagn Microbiol Infect Dis | volume = 86 | issue = | page = 257 | doi = 10.1016/j.diagmicrobio.2016.08.001 | pmid = 27568365 }}</ref> MALDI can also detect [[carbapenemase]] of [[carbapenem-resistant enterobacteriaceae]],<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vogne | first1 = C. | display-authors = etal | year = 2014 | title = \"A simple, robust and rapid approach to detect carbapenemases in Gram-negative isolates by MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry \" validation with triple quadripole tandem mass spectrometry, microarray and PCR | url = | journal = Clin Microbiol Infect | volume = 20 | issue = | pages = O1106-12| doi = 10.1111/1469-0691 | pmid = 24930405 }}</ref> including ''[[Acinetobacter baumannii]]'' <ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 28303824 | doi=10.4103/0255-0857.202335 | volume=35 | title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionisation time-of-flight mass spectrometry rapid detection of carbapenamase activity in ''Acinetobacter baumannii'' isolates | year=2017 | journal=Indian J Med Microbiol | pages=85\u201389 | last1 = Abouseada | first1 = N | last2 = Raouf | first2 = M | last3 = El-Attar | first3 = E | last4 = Moez | first4 = P}}</ref> and ''[[Klebsiella pneumoniae]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sakarikou | first1 = C | last2 = Ciotti | first2 = M | last3 = Dolfa | first3 = C | last4 = Angeletti | first4 = S | last5 = Favalli | first5 = C | year = 2017 | title = Rapid detection of carbapenemase-producing Klebsiella pneumoniae strains derived from blood cultures by Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization-Time of Flight Mass Spectrometry (MALDI-TOF MS) | journal = BMC Microbiol | volume = 17 | issue = 1| page = 54 | doi = 10.1186/s12866-017-0952-3 | pmid = 28274205 | pmc = 5343375 }}</ref>\nHowever, most proteins that mediate antibiotic resistance are larger than MALDI-TOF's 2000-20,000 Da range for protein peak interpretation and only occasionally, as in the 2011 KPC outbreak at the NIH, a correlation between a peak and resistance conferring protein can be made.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lau | first1 = A. | display-authors = etal | date = August 2014 | title = A Rapid Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization\u2013Time of Flight Mass Spectrometry-Based Method for Single-Plasmid Tracking in an Outbreak of Carbapenem-Resistant Enterobacteriaceae | url = | journal = Journal of Clinical Microbiology | volume = 52 | issue = 8| pages = 2804\u20132812 | doi = 10.1128/JCM.00694-14 | pmid = 4136129 }}</ref>\n\n===Parasitology===\nMALDI/TOF spectra have been used for the detection and identification of various parasites such as [[trypanosomatid]]s,<ref name=\"AvilaAlmeida2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Avila|first1=C. C.|last2=Almeida|first2=F. G.|last3=Palmisano|first3=G.|title=Direct identification of trypanosomatids by matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization-time of flight mass spectrometry (DIT MALDI-TOF MS)|journal=Journal of Mass Spectrometry|volume=51|issue=8|year=2016|pages=549\u2013557|issn=1076-5174|doi=10.1002/jms.3763|pmid=27659938|bibcode=2016JMSp...51..549A}}</ref> ''[[Leishmania]]'' <ref name=\"LachaudFern\u00e1ndez-Ar\u00e9valo2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Lachaud|first1=Laurence|last2=Fern\u00e1ndez-Ar\u00e9valo|first2=Anna|last3=Normand|first3=Anne-C\u00e9cile|last4=Lami|first4=Patrick|last5=Nabet|first5=C\u00e9cile|last6=Donnadieu|first6=Jean Luc|last7=Piarroux|first7=Martine|last8=Djenad|first8=Farid|last9=Cassagne|first9=Carole|last10=Ravel|first10=Christophe|last11=Tebar|first11=Silvia|last12=Llovet|first12=Teresa|last13=Blanchet|first13=Denis|last14=Demar|first14=Magalie|last15=Harrat|first15=Zoubir|last16=Aoun|first16=Karim|last17=Bastien|first17=Patrick|last18=Mu\u00f1oz|first18=Carmen|last19=G\u00e1llego|first19=Montserrat|last20=Piarroux|first20=Renaud|last21=Loeffelholz|first21=Michael J.|title=Identification of ''Leishmania'' by Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization\u2013Time of Flight (MALDI-TOF) Mass Spectrometry Using a Free Web-Based Application and a Dedicated Mass-Spectral Library|journal=Journal of Clinical Microbiology|volume=55|issue=10|year=2017|pages=2924\u20132933|issn=0095-1137|doi=10.1128/JCM.00845-17|pmid=28724559|pmc=5625378}}</ref> and ''[[Plasmodium]]''.<ref name=\"LarocheAlmeras2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Laroche|first1=Maureen|last2=Almeras|first2=Lionel|last3=Pecchi|first3=Emilie|last4=Bechah|first4=Yassina|last5=Raoult|first5=Didier|last6=Viola|first6=Ang\u00e8le|last7=Parola|first7=Philippe|title=MALDI-TOF MS as an innovative tool for detection of ''Plasmodium'' parasites in ''Anopheles'' mosquitoes|journal=Malaria Journal|volume=16|issue=1|pages=5|year=2017|issn=1475-2875|doi=10.1186/s12936-016-1657-z|pmid=28049524|pmc=5209920}}</ref>\nIn addition to these [[unicellular]] parasites, MALDI/TOF can be used for the identification of [[cercariae]], the free-swimming stage of [[trematode]]s.<ref name=\"HugueninDepaquit2019\">{{cite journal|last1=Huguenin|first1=Antoine|last2=Depaquit|first2=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|last3=Villena|first3=Isabelle|last4=Fert\u00e9|first4=Hubert|title=MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry: a new tool for rapid identification of cercariae (Trematoda, Digenea)|journal=Parasite|volume=26|year=2019|pages=11|issn=1776-1042|doi=10.1051/parasite/2019011|url=https://www.parasite-journal.org/articles/parasite/full_html/2019/01/parasite180154/parasite180154.html|pmid= 30838972| pmc=6402365 }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\nMALDI/TOF spectra are often utilized in tandem with other analysis and spectroscopy techniques in the diagnosis of diseases. MALDI/TOF is a diagnostic tool with much potential because it allows for the rapid identification of proteins and changes to proteins without the cost or computing power of [[Next-generation sequencing|sequencing]] nor the skill or time needed to solve a crystal structure in [[X-ray crystallography]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nOne example of this is [[necrotizing enterocolitis]] (NEC), which is a devastating disease that affects the bowels of premature infants. The symptoms of NEC are very similar to those of [[sepsis]], and many infants die awaiting diagnosis and treatment. MALDI/TOF was used to quickly analyze fecal samples and find differences between the mutant and the functional protein responsible for NEC. There is hope that a similar technique could be used as a quick, diagnostic tool that would not require sequencing.<ref>Sim, K.; Shaw, A. G.; Randell, P.; Cox, M. J.; McClure, Z. E.; Li, M. S.; Haddad, M.; Langford, P. R.; Cookson, W. O.; Moffatt, M. F.; Kroll, J. S. Dysbiosis anticipating necrotizing enterocolitis in very premature infants. Clin. Infect. Dis. 2014.</ref>\n\nAnother example of the diagnostic power of MALDI/TOF is in the area of [[cancer]]. [[Pancreatic cancer]] remains one of the most deadly and difficult to diagnose cancers.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grantzdorffer | first1 = I | last2 = Carl-McGrath | first2 = S | last3 = Ebert | first3 = MP | last4 = Rocken | first4 = C | year = 2008 | title = Proteomics of pancreatic cancer | url = | journal = Pancreas | volume = 36 | issue = 4| pages = 329\u201336 | doi = 10.1097/MPA.0b013e31815cc452 }}</ref> Impaired [[cellular signaling]] due to mutations in membrane proteins has been long suspected to contribute to pancreatic cancer.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dhillon | first1 = AS | last2 = Hagan | first2 = S | last3 = Rath | first3 = O | last4 = Kolch | first4 = W | year = 2007 | title = MAP kinase signalling pathways in cancer | url = | journal = Oncogene | volume = 26 | issue = 22| pages = 3279\u201390 | doi = 10.1038/sj.onc.1210421 }}</ref> MALDI/TOF has been used to identify a [[membrane protein]] associated with pancreatic cancer and at one point may even serve as an early detection technique.<ref>Zhong, N.; Cui, Y.; Zhou, X.; Li, T.; Han, J. Identification of prohibitin 1 as a potential prognostic biomarker in human pancreatic carcinoma using modified aqueous two-phase partition system combined with 2D-MALDI-TOF-TOF-MS/MS. Tumour Biol. 2014.</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2017}}\n\nMALDI/TOF can also potentially be used to dictate treatment as well as diagnosis. MALDI/TOF serves as a method for determining the [[drug resistance]] of bacteria, especially to [[Beta-lactam antibiotic|\u03b2-lactams]] (Penicillin family). The MALDI/TOF detects the presence of carbapenemases, which indicates drug resistance to standard antibiotics. It is predicted that this could serve as a method for identifying a bacterium as drug resistant in as little as three hours. This technique could help physicians decide whether to prescribe more aggressive antibiotics initially.<ref>Hrab\u00e1k, Jaroslav (2015). \"Detection of Carbapenemases Using Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry (MALDI-TOF MS) Meropenem Hydrolysis Assay\". Methods in Molecular Biology (1064-3745), 1237, p. 91.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Peptide mass fingerprinting]]\n* [[PEGylation]]\n* [[MALDI imaging]]\n*[[Matrix (mass spectrometry)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Ragoussis |first1=J. |last2=Elvidge |first2=G. P. |last3=Kaur |first3=K. |last4=Colella |first4=S. |year=2006 |title=Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionisation, Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry in Genomics Research |journal=[[PLoS Genetics]] |volume=2 |issue=7 |pages=e100 |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.0020100 |pmc=1523240 |pmid=16895448 }} \n*{{cite journal |last1=Hardouin |first1=J. |year=2007 |title=Protein sequence information by matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization in-source decay mass spectrometry |journal=[[Mass Spectrometry Reviews]] |volume=26 |issue=5 |pages=672\u201382 |doi=10.1002/mas.20142 |pmid=17492750 |bibcode=2007MSRv...26..672H }} \n*{{cite book |last1=Peter-Katalinic |first1=J. |last2=Hillenkamp |first2=F. |year=2007 |title=MALDI MS: A Practical Guide to Instrumentation, Methods and Applications |publisher=[[Wiley-VCH]] |isbn=978-3-527-31440-9 }} \n*{{cite book |last1=Schrepp |first1=W. |last2=Pasch |first2=H. |year=2003 |title=MALDI-TOF Mass Spectrometry of Synthetic Polymers |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |isbn=978-3-540-44259-2 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091102022351/http://www.magnet.fsu.edu/education/tutorials/tools/ionization_maldi.html Primer on Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization (MALDI)] National High Magnetic Field Laboratory\n\n{{Mass spectrometry}}\n{{lasers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization}}\n[[Category:Ion source]]\n[[Category:Biochemistry methods]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:MALDITOF.jpg|thumb|right|200 px|MALDI TOF mass spectrometer]]\nIn [[mass spectrometry]], '''matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization''' ('''MALDI''') is an [[ionization]] technique that uses a laser energy absorbing  matrix to create [[ion]]s from large [[molecule]]s with minimal fragmentation.<ref name=\"HillenkampKaras1991\">{{cite journal|last1=Hillenkamp|first1=Franz|last2=Karas|first2=Michael|last3=Beavis|first3=Ronald C.|last4=Chait|first4=Brian T.|title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry of biopolymers|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=63|issue=24|year=1991|pages=1193A\u20131203A|issn=0003-2700|doi=10.1021/ac00024a002|pmid=1789447}}</ref> It has been applied to the analysis of [[biomolecule]]s ([[biopolymer]]s such as [[DNA]], [[protein]]s, [[peptide]]s and [[sugar]]s) and large [[organic chemistry|organic]] [[molecule]]s (such as [[polymer]]s, [[dendrimer]]s and other [[macromolecule]]s), which tend to be fragile and fragment when ionized by more conventional ionization methods. It is similar in character to [[electrospray ionization]] (ESI) in that both techniques are relatively soft (low fragmentation) ways of obtaining ions of large molecules in the gas phase, though MALDI typically produces far fewer multi-charged ions.\n\nMALDI methodology is a three-step process. First, the sample is mixed with a suitable matrix material and applied to a metal plate. Second, a pulsed [[laser]] irradiates the sample, triggering [[ablation]] and [[desorption]] of the sample and matrix material. Finally, the analyte molecules are ionized by being [[protonation|protonated]] or [[deprotonation|deprotonated]] in the hot plume of ablated gases, and then they can be accelerated into whichever mass spectrometer is used to analyse them.<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Karas|first1=Michael|last2=Kr\u00fcger|first2=Ralf|title=Ion Formation in MALDI: The Cluster Ionization Mechanism|journal=Chemical Reviews|volume=103|issue=2|year=2003|pages=427\u2013440|issn=0009-2665|doi=10.1021/cr010376a|pmid=12580637}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{main|History of mass spectrometry}}\n\nThe term matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI) was coined in 1985 by [[Franz Hillenkamp]], [[Michael Karas]] and their colleagues.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Bachmann |first2=D. |last3=Hillenkamp |first3=F. |year=1985 |title=Influence of the Wavelength in High-Irradiance Ultraviolet Laser Desorption Mass Spectrometry of Organic Molecules |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=57 |issue=14 |pages=2935\u20139 |doi=10.1021/ac00291a042 }}</ref> These researchers found that the [[amino acid]] [[alanine]] could be ionized more easily if it was mixed with the amino acid [[tryptophan]] and irradiated with a pulsed 266&nbsp;nm laser. The tryptophan was absorbing the laser energy and helping to ionize the non-absorbing alanine. Peptides up to the 2843 [[Dalton (unit)|Da]] peptide [[melittin]] could be ionized when mixed with this kind of \"matrix\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Bachmann |first2=D. |last3=Bahr |first3=U. |last4=Hillenkamp |first4=F. |year=1987 |title=Matrix-Assisted Ultraviolet Laser Desorption of Non-Volatile Compounds |journal=[[International Journal of Mass Spectrometry and Ion Processes]] |volume=78 |issue= |pages=53\u201368 |doi=10.1016/0168-1176(87)87041-6 |bibcode = 1987IJMSI..78...53K }}</ref> The breakthrough for large molecule laser desorption ionization came in 1987 when [[Koichi Tanaka]] of Shimadzu Corporation and his co-workers used what they called the \"ultra fine metal plus liquid matrix method\" that combined 30&nbsp;nm [[cobalt]] particles in [[glycerol]] with a 337&nbsp;nm [[nitrogen laser]] for ionization.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tanaka |first1=K. |last2=Waki |first2=H. |last3=Ido |first3=Y. |last4=Akita |first4=S. |last5=Yoshida |first5=Y. |last6=Yoshida |first6=T. |last7=Matsuo |first7=T. |year=1988 |title=Protein and Polymer Analyses up to ''m''/''z'' 100&nbsp;000 by Laser Ionization Time-of flight Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=2 |issue=20 |pages=151\u20133 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290020802 |bibcode=1988RCMS....2..151T }}</ref> Using this laser and matrix combination, Tanaka was able to ionize biomolecules as large as the 34,472 Da protein carboxypeptidase-A. Tanaka received one-quarter of the 2002 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] for demonstrating that, with the proper combination of laser wavelength and matrix, a protein can be ionized.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markides |first1=K. |last2=Gr\u00e4slund |first2=A. |date=9 October 2002 |title=Advanced information on the Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2002 |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/2002/advanced-chemistryprize2002.pdf |pages=1\u201313 |publisher=[[The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]] |accessdate=2013-08-28 }}</ref> Karas and Hillenkamp were subsequently able to ionize the 67 kDa protein albumin using a nicotinic acid matrix and a 266&nbsp;nm laser.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Hillenkamp |first2=F. |year=1988 |title=Laser desorption ionization of proteins with molecular masses exceeding 10,000 daltons |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=60 |issue=20 |pages=2299\u2013301 |doi=10.1021/ac00171a028 |pmid=3239801 }}</ref> Further improvements were realized through the use of a 355&nbsp;nm laser and the [[cinnamic acid]] derivatives [[ferulic acid]], [[caffeic acid]] and [[sinapinic acid]] as the matrix.<ref name=\"Beavis 1989\" /> The availability of small and relatively inexpensive [[nitrogen laser]]s operating at 337&nbsp;nm wavelength and the first commercial instruments introduced in the early 1990s brought MALDI to an increasing number of researchers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karas |first1=M. |last2=Bahr |first2=U. |year=1990 |title=Laser Desorption Ionization Mass Spectrometry of Large Biomolecules |journal=[[Trends in Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=9 |issue=10 |pages=321\u20135 |doi=10.1016/0165-9936(90)85065-F }}</ref> Today, mostly organic matrices are used for MALDI mass spectrometry.\n\n==Matrix ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style = \"float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:15px; width:40%\"\n|+ '''UV MALDI Matrix List'''\n! Compound !! Other Names !! Solvent !! Wavelength (nm) !! Applications\n|-\n! [[Gentisic acid|2,5-dihydroxy benzoic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Strupat |first=K. |last2=Karas |first2=M. |last3=Hillenkamp |first3=F. |year=1991 |title=2,5-Dihidroxybenzoic acid: A new matrix for laser desorption\u2014ionization mass spectrometry |journal=[[International Journal of Mass Spectrometry and Ion Processes]] |volume=72 |issue=111 |pages=89\u2013102 |bibcode=1991IJMSI.111...89S |doi=10.1016/0168-1176(91)85050-V }}</ref>\n| DHB, [[Gentisic acid]] || [[acetonitrile]], [[water]], [[methanol]], [[acetone]], [[chloroform]] || 337, 355, 266 || [[peptide]]s, [[nucleotide]]s, [[oligonucleotide]]s, [[oligosaccharide]]s\n|-\n! [[sinapinic acid|3,5-dimethoxy-4-hydroxycinnamic acid]]<ref name=\"Beavis 1989\">{{cite journal |last1=Beavis |first1=R. C. |last2=Chait |first2=B. T. |last3=Standing |first3=K. G. |year=1989 |title=Matrix-assisted laser-desorption mass spectrometry using 355&nbsp;nm radiation |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=436\u20139 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290031208 |pmid=2520224 |bibcode=1989RCMS....3..436B }}</ref><ref name=\"Beavis 1989a\">{{cite journal |last1=Beavis |first1=R. C. |last2=Chait |first2=B. T. |last3=Fales |first3=H. M. |year=1989 |title=Cinnamic acid derivatives as matrices for ultraviolet laser desorption mass spectrometry of proteins |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=432\u20135 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290031207 |pmid=2520223 |bibcode=1989RCMS....3..432B }}</ref>\n| sinapic acid; [[sinapinic acid]]; SA || [[acetonitrile]], water, acetone, chloroform || 337, 355, 266 || peptides, proteins, [[lipid]]s\n|-\n! [[ferulic acid|4-hydroxy-3-methoxycinnamic acid]]<ref name=\"Beavis 1989\" /><ref name=\"Beavis 1989a\" />\n| [[ferulic acid]]|| [[acetonitrile]], water, [[propanol]] || 337, 355, 266 || proteins \n|-\n! [[alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid|\u03b1-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Beavis |first1=R. C. |last2=Chaudhary |first2=T. |last3=Chait |first3=B. T. |year=1992 |title=\u03b1-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid as a matrix for matrix-assisted laser desorption mass spectrometry |journal=[[Organic Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=156\u20138 |doi=10.1002/oms.1210270217 }}</ref>\n| CHCA || [[acetonitrile]], water, [[ethanol]], acetone || 337, 355 ||peptides, lipids, nucleotides\n|-\n! [[Picolinic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tang |first1=K. |last2=Taranenko |first2=N. I. |last3=Allman |first3=S. L. |last4=Ch\u00e1ng |first4=L. Y. |last5=Chen |first5=C. H. |last6=Lubman |first6=D. M. |year=1994 |title=Detection of 500-nucleotide DNA by laser desorption mass spectrometry |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=8 |issue=9 |pages=727\u201330 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290080913 |pmid=7949335 |bibcode=1994RCMS....8..727T }}</ref>\n| PA || Ethanol || 266 || oligonucleotides\n|-\n! [[3-hydroxy picolinic acid]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wu |first1=K. J. |last2=Steding |first2=A. |last3=Becker |first3=C. H. |year=1993 |title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption time-of-flight mass spectrometry of oligonucleotides using 3-hydroxypicolinic acid as an ultraviolet-sensitive matrix |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=142\u20136 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290070206 |pmid=8457722 |bibcode=1993RCMS....7..142W }}</ref>\n|| HPA|| Ethanol || 337, 355 || oligonucleotides\n|}\n\nThe [[matrix (mass spectrometry)|matrix]] consists of [[crystal]]lized molecules, of which the three most commonly used are 3,5-dimethoxy-4-hydroxycinnamic [[acid]] ([[sinapinic acid]]), [[alpha-Cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid|\u03b1-cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid]] (\u03b1-CHCA, alpha-cyano or alpha-matrix) and [[2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid]] (DHB).<ref>{{Cite book|title = Using Mass Spectrometry for Drug Metabolism Studies|last = Korfmacher|first = Walter A.|publisher = CRC Press|year = 2009|isbn = 9781420092219|location = |page = 342|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=C0nzGNCHhL8C&pg=PA342}}</ref> A [[solution]] of one of these molecules is made, often in a mixture of highly purified [[water]] and an organic [[solvent]] such as [[acetonitrile]] (ACN) or [[ethanol]]. A counter ion source such as [[Trifluoroacetic acid]] (TFA) is usually added to generate the [M+H] ions. A good example of a matrix-solution would be 20 [[Milligram per liter|mg/mL]] sinapinic acid in ACN:water:TFA (50:50:0.1).\n\n[[Image:Cinnamic acid substitutions.PNG|left|thumb|250 px|Notation for cinnamic acid substitutions.]]\nThe identification of suitable matrix compounds is determined to some extent by trial and error, but they are based on some specific molecular design considerations. They are of a fairly low molecular weight (to allow easy vaporization), but are large enough (with a low enough vapor pressure) not to evaporate during sample preparation or while standing in the mass spectrometer. They are often acidic, therefore act as a proton source to encourage ionization of the analyte. Basic matrices have also been reported.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Fitzgerald |first1=M. C. |last2=Parr |first2=G. R. |last3=Smith |first3=L. M. |year=1993 |title=Basic matrixes for the matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry of proteins and oligonucleotides |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=65 |issue=22 |pages=3204\u201311 |doi=10.1021/ac00070a007 |pmid=8291672 }}</ref> They have a strong optical absorption in either the UV or IR range,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Zenobi |first1=R. |last2=Knochenmuss |first2=R. |year=1998 |title=Ion formation in MALDI mass spectrometry |journal=[[Mass Spectrometry Reviews]] |volume=17 |pages=337\u2013366 |issue=5 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2787(1998)17:5<337::AID-MAS2>3.0.CO;2-S |bibcode=1998MSRv...17..337Z }}</ref> so that they rapidly and efficiently absorb the laser irradiation. This efficiency is commonly associated with chemical structures incorporating several [[conjugated double bond]]s, as seen in the structure of [[cinnamic acid]]. They are functionalized with polar groups, allowing their use in aqueous solutions. They typically contain a chromophore.\n\nThe matrix solution is mixed with the analyte (e.g. [[protein]]-sample). A mixture of water and organic solvent allows both [[hydrophobic]] and water-soluble ([[hydrophilic]]) molecules to dissolve into the solution. This solution is spotted onto a MALDI plate (usually a metal plate designed for this purpose). The solvents vaporize, leaving only the recrystallized matrix, but now with analyte molecules embedded into MALDI crystals. The matrix and the analyte are said to be co-crystallized. Co-crystallization is a key issue in selecting a proper matrix to obtain a good quality mass spectrum of the analyte of interest.\n\nIn analysis of biological systems, Inorganic salts, which are also part of protein extracts, interfere with the ionization process. The salts can be removed by solid phase extraction or by washing the dried-droplet MALDI spots with cold water.<ref name=\"XuBruening2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=Yingda|last2=Bruening|first2=Merlin L.|last3=Watson|first3=J. Throck|title=Non-specific, on-probe cleanup methods for MALDI-MS samples|journal=Mass Spectrometry Reviews|volume=22|issue=6|year=2003|pages=429\u2013440|issn=0277-7037|doi=10.1002/mas.10064|pmid=14528495|bibcode=2003MSRv...22..429X}}</ref> Both methods can also remove other substances from the sample. The matrix-protein mixture is not homogenous because the polarity difference leads to a separation of the two substances during co-crystallization. The spot diameter of the target is much larger than that of the laser, which makes it necessary to make many laser shots at different places of the target, to get the statistical average of the substance concentration within the target spot.\n\n[[File:Naphthalene.png|thumbnail|right|Naphthalene and naphthalene-like compounds can also be used as a matrix to ionize a sample]]\nThe matrix can be used to tune the instrument to ionize the sample in different ways. As mentioned above, acid-base like reactions are often utilized to ionize the sample, however, molecules with conjugated pi systems, such as naphthalene like compounds, can also serve as an electron acceptor and thus a matrix for MALDI/TOF.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nazim Boutaghou | first1 = M. | last2 = Cole | first2 = R. B. | year = 2012 | title = 9,10-Diphenylanthracene as a matrix for MALDI-MS electron transfer secondary reactions | url = | journal = J. Mass Spectrom | volume = 47 | issue = | pages = 995\u20131003 | doi = 10.1002/jms.3027 }}</ref> This is particularly useful in studying molecules that also possess [[Conjugated system|conjugated pi systems]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Suzuki | first1 = T. | last2 = Midonoya | first2 = H. | last3 = Shioi | first3 = Y. | year = 2009 | title = Analysis of chlorophylls and their derivatives by matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization\u2013time-of-flight mass spectrometry | url = | journal = Anal. Biochem | volume = 390 | issue = | pages = 57\u201362 | doi = 10.1016/j.ab.2009.04.005 }}</ref> The most widely used application for these matrices is studying porphyrin like compounds such as [[chlorophyll]]. These matrices have been shown to have better ionization patterns that do not result in odd fragmentation patterns or complete loss of side chains.<ref>Wei, J.; Li, H.; Barrow, M. P.; O'Connor, P. B. Structural characterization of chlorophyll-a by high resolution tandem mass spectrometry. J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom. 2013, 24, 753-760.</ref> It has also been suggested that conjugated porphryin like molecules can serve as a matrix and cleave themselves eliminating the need for a separate matrix compound.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Srinivasan | first1 = N. | last2 = Haney | first2 = C. A. | last3 = Lindsey | first3 = J. S. | last4 = Zhang | first4 = W. | last5 = Chait | first5 = B. T. | year = 1999 | title = Investigation of MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry of diverse synthetic metalloporphyrins, phthalocyanines and multiporphyrin arrays | url = | journal = J. Porphyrins Phthalocyanines | volume = 3 | issue = | pages = 283\u2013291 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1099-1409(199904)3:4<283::AID-JPP132>3.0.CO;2-F }}</ref>\n\n==Instrumentation==\n[[File:MALDI TOF EN.png|thumb|Diagram of a MALDI TOF instrument. Sample matrix ionized by radiant energy is ejected from surface. Sample travels into mass analyzer and is substantially detected.]]\nThere are several variations of the MALDI technology and comparable instruments are today produced for very different purposes. From more academic and analytical, to more industrial and high throughput. The MS field has expanded into requiring ultrahigh resolution mass spectrometry such as the FT-ICR instruments<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biocompare.com/Editorial-Articles/41589-Talking-About-a-Revolution-FT-ICR-Mass-Spectrometry-Offers-High-Resolution-and-Mass-Accuracy-for-Pr/|title=Talking About a Revolution: FT-ICR Mass Spectrometry Offers High Resolution and Mass Accuracy for Pr}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 2129108 | pages=1309\u20131310 | volume=389 | issue=5 | journal=Anal Bioanal Chem | title=Ultrahigh resolution mass spectrometry | doi=10.1007/s00216-007-1589-0| year=2007 | last1=Schmitt-Kopplin | first1=P | last2=Hertkorn | first2=N }}</ref> as well as more high-throughput instruments.<ref>{{cite journal |journal= Journal of Microbiological Methods |volume= 86|issue= 3|date= September 2011| pages= 327\u2013336|doi=10.1016/j.mimet.2011.06.004|pmid = 21699925|title=Evaluation of MALDI-TOF MS as a tool for high-throughput dereplication|last1= Ghyselinck |first1= Jonas |last2= Van Hoorde |first2= Koenraad |last3= Hoste |first3= Bart |last4= Heylen |first4= Kim |last5= De Vos |first5= Paul }}</ref> As many MALDI MS instruments can be bought with an interchangeable ionization source ([[Electrospray ionization]], MALDI, [[Atmospheric pressure ionization]], etc.) the technologies often overlap and many times any soft ionization method could potentially be used. For more variations of soft ionization methods go to [[Soft laser desorption]] or [[Ion source]].\n\n===Laser===\nMALDI techniques typically employ the use of UV [[lasers]] such as nitrogen lasers (337&nbsp;nm) and frequency-tripled and quadrupled [[Nd:YAG lasers]] (355&nbsp;nm and 266&nbsp;nm respectively).<ref name=\"Dreisewerd2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Dreisewerd|first1=Klaus|title=Recent methodological advances in MALDI mass spectrometry|journal=Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry|volume=406|issue=9\u201310|year=2014|pages=2261\u20132278|issn=1618-2642|doi=10.1007/s00216-014-7646-6|pmid=24652146}}</ref>\n\nInfrared laser wavelengths used for infrared MALDI include the 2.94&nbsp;\u03bcm [[Er:YAG laser]], mid-IR [[optical parametric oscillator]], and 10.6&nbsp;\u03bcm [[carbon dioxide laser]]. Although not as common, infrared lasers are used due to their softer mode of ionization.<ref>{{cite book |last=Murray |first1=K |chapter-url=https://www.elsevier.com/books/the-encyclopedia-of-mass-spectrometry/gross/978-0-08-043801-6 |title=The Encyclopedia of Mass Spectrometry |chapter=Chapter 9 Desorption by Photons: Laser Desorption and Matridx-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization (MALDI) \u2013 Infrared Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization |volume=Volume 6: Ionization Methods |editor-last=Gross |editor-first=Michael L. |editor2-last=Caprioli |editor2-first=Richard M. |work= |publisher=Elsevier Science |year=2006 |isbn=9780080438016 |accessdate=2017-04-05 }}</ref> IR-MALDI also has the advantage of greater material removal (useful for biological samples), less low-mass interferences, and compatibility with other matrix-free laser desorption mass spectrometry methods.\n\n=== Time of flight ===\n[[Image:MALDI Target.jpg|thumb|right|300 px|Sample target for a MALDI mass spectrometer]]\nThe type of a mass spectrometer most widely used with MALDI is the [[Time-of-flight mass spectrometry|TOF]] (time-of-flight mass spectrometer), mainly due to its large mass range. The TOF measurement procedure is also ideally suited to the MALDI ionization process since the pulsed laser takes individual 'shots' rather than working in continuous operation. MALDI-TOF instruments are often equipped with a [[reflectron]] (an \"ion mirror\")  that reflects ions using an electric field. This increases the ion flight path, thereby increasing time of flight between ions of different m/z and increasing resolution. Modern commercial [[reflectron]] TOF instruments reach a resolving power m/\u0394m of 50,000 FWHM (full-width half-maximum, \u0394m defined as the peak width at 50% of peak height) or more.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xian|first=Feng|last2=Hendrickson|first2=Christopher L.|last3=Marshall|first3=Alan G.|date=2012-01-17|title=High Resolution Mass Spectrometry|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=84|issue=2|pages=708\u2013719|doi=10.1021/ac203191t|pmid=22263633|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>\n\nMALDI has been coupled with [[Ion-mobility spectrometry\u2013mass spectrometry|IMS]]-TOF MS to identify phosphorylated and non-phosphorylated peptides.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ruotolo |first1=B. T. |last2=Gillig |first2=K. J. |last3=Woods |first3=A. S. |last4=Egan |first4=T. F. |last5=Ugarov |first5=M. V. |last6=Schultz |first6=J. A. |last7=Russell |first7=D. H. |year=2004 |title=Analysis of Phosphorylated Peptides by Ion Mobility-Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=76 |issue=22 |pages=6727\u20136733 |doi=10.1021/ac0498009 |pmid=15538797 }}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ruotolo |first1=B. T. |last2=Verbeck |first2=G. F. |last3=Thomson |first3=L. M. |last4=Woods |first4=A. S. |last5=Gillig |first5=K. J. |last6=Russell |first6=D. H. |year=2002 |title=Distinguishing between Phosphorylated and Nonphosphorylated Peptides with Ion Mobility\u2212Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Journal of Proteome Research]] |volume=1 |issue=4|pages=303\u2013306 |doi=10.1021/pr025516r }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nMALDI-[[FT-ICR]] MS has been demonstrated to be a useful technique where high resolution MALDI-MS measurements are desired.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pasa-Tolic |first1=L. |last2=Huang |first2=Y. |last3=Guan |first3=S. |last4=Kim |first4=H. S. |last5=Marshall |first5=A. G. |year=1995 |title=Ultrahigh-resolution matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectra of peptides |journal=[[Journal of Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=30 |issue=6 |pages=825\u2013833 |doi=10.1002/jms.1190300607 |bibcode=1995JMSp...30..825P }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n=== Atmospheric pressure ===\nAtmospheric pressure (AP) matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI) is an ionization technique (ion source) that in contrast to vacuum MALDI operates at normal atmospheric environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Laiko |first1=V. V. |last2=Baldwin |first2=M. A. |last3=Burlingame |first3=A. L. |year=2000 |title=Atmospheric pressure matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=72 |issue=4 |pages=652\u20137 |pmid=10701247 |doi=10.1021/ac990998k }}</ref> The main difference between vacuum MALDI and AP-MALDI is the pressure in which the ions are created. In vacuum MALDI, ions are typically produced at 10 mTorr or less while in AP-MALDI ions are formed in [[atmospheric pressure]]. In the past the main disadvantage of AP MALDI technique compared to the conventional vacuum MALDI has been its limited sensitivity; however, ions can be transferred into the mass spectrometer with high efficiency and attomole detection limits have been reported.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strupat |first1=K. |last2=Scheibner |first2=O. |last3=Arrey |first3=T. |last4=Bromirski |first4=M. |year=2011 |title=Biological Applications of AP MALDI with Thermo Scientific Exactive Orbitrap MS |url=http://www.apmaldi.com/images/stories/005-111101-an30224-maldi-generalapp_6s_v4a_kp.pdf |work=443-539-1710 |publisher=[[Thermo Scientific]] |accessdate=17 June 2011 }}</ref> AP-MALDI is used in mass spectrometry (MS) in a variety of applications ranging from proteomics to drug discovery. Popular topics that are addressed by AP-MALDI mass spectrometry include: proteomics; mass analysis of DNA, RNA, PNA, lipids, oligosaccharides, phosphopeptides, bacteria, small molecules and synthetic polymers, similar applications as available also for vacuum MALDI instruments. The AP-MALDI ion source is easily coupled to an ion trap mass spectrometer<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Laiko |first1=V. V. |last2=Moyer |first2=S. C. |last3=Cotter |first3=R. J. |year=2000 |title=Atmospheric pressure MALDI/ion trap mass spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=72 |issue=21 |pages=5239\u201343 |doi=10.1021/ac000530d |pmid=11080870 }}</ref> or any other MS system equipped with [[Electrospray ionization|ESI]] (electrospray ionization) or nanoESI source.\n\n===Aerosol===\nIn [[aerosol mass spectrometry]], one of the ionization techniques consists in firing a laser to individual droplets. These systems are called [[Aerosol mass spectrometry#Single-particle measurements|single particle mass spectrometers (SPMS)]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Yong Jie |last2=Sun |first2=Yele |last3=Zhang |first3=Qi |last4=Li |first4=Xue |last5=Li |first5=Mei |last6=Zhou |first6=Zhen |last7=Chan |first7=Chak K. |title=Real-time chemical characterization of atmospheric particulate matter in China: A review |journal=Atmospheric Environment |date=June 2017 |volume=158 |pages=270\u2013304 |doi=10.1016/j.atmosenv.2017.02.027|bibcode=2017AtmEn.158..270L }}</ref> The sample may optionally be mixed with a MALDI matrix prior to aerosolization.\n\n==Ionization mechanism==\nThe [[laser]] is fired at the matrix crystals in the dried-droplet spot. The matrix absorbs the laser energy and it is thought that primarily the matrix is desorbed and ionized (by addition of a [[proton]]) by this event. The hot plume produced during ablation contains many species: neutral and ionized matrix molecules, protonated and deprotonated matrix molecules, matrix clusters and [[Droplet|nanodroplets]]. Ablated species may participate in the ionization of analyte, though the mechanism of MALDI is still debated. The matrix is then thought to transfer protons to the analyte molecules (e.g., protein molecules), thus charging the analyte.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Knochenmuss |first=R |year=2006 |title=Ion formation mechanisms in UV-MALDI |journal=[[Analyst (journal)|Analyst]] |volume=131 |issue=9 |pages=966\u2013986 |bibcode=2006Ana...131..966K |doi=10.1039/b605646f |pmid=17047796 }}</ref> An ion observed after this process will consist of the initial neutral molecule [M] with ions added or removed. This is called a quasimolecular ion, for example [M+H]<sup>+</sup> in the case of an added proton, [M+Na]<sup>+</sup> in the case of an added [[sodium]] ion, or [M-H]<sup>\u2212</sup> in the case of a removed proton. MALDI is capable of creating singly charged ions or multiply charged ions ([M+nH]<sup>n+</sup>) depending on the nature of the matrix, the laser intensity, and/or the voltage used. Note that these are all even-electron species. Ion signals of radical cations (photoionized molecules) can be observed, e.g., in the case of matrix molecules and other organic molecules.\n\nThe gas phase proton transfer model,<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\" /> implemented as the coupled physical and chemical dynamics (CPCD) model,<ref name=\"Knochenmuss2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Knochenmuss|first1=Richard|title=The Coupled Chemical and Physical Dynamics Model of MALDI|journal=Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry|volume=9|issue=1|year=2016|pages=365\u2013385|issn=1936-1327|doi=10.1146/annurev-anchem-071015-041750|pmid=27070182|bibcode=2016ARAC....9..365K}}</ref> of UV laser MALDI postulates primary and secondary processes leading to ionization.<ref name=\"Knochenmuss2006\">{{cite journal|last1=Knochenmuss|first1=Richard|title=Ion formation mechanisms in UV-MALDI|journal=The Analyst|volume=131|issue=9|year=2006|pages=966\u201386|issn=0003-2654|doi=10.1039/b605646f|pmid=17047796|bibcode=2006Ana...131..966K}}</ref> Primary processes involve initial charge separation through absorption of photons by the matrix and pooling of the energy to form matrix ion pairs. Primary ion formation occurs through absorption of a UV photon to create excited state molecules by\n\n:S<sub>0</sub> + h\u03bd \u2192 S<sub>1</sub>\n\n:S<sub>1</sub> + S<sub>1</sub> \u2192 S<sub>0</sub> + S<sub>n</sub>\n\n:S<sub>1</sub> + S<sub>n</sub> \u2192 M<sup>+</sup> + M<sup>\u2212</sup>\n\nwhere S<sub>0</sub> is the ground electronic state, S<sub>1</sub> the first electronic excited state, and S<sub>n</sub> is a higher electronic excited state.<ref name=\"Knochenmuss2016\" /> The product ions can be proton transfer or electron transfer ion pairs, indicated by M<sup>+</sup> and M<sup>\u2212</sup> above. Secondary processes involve ion-molecule reactions to form analyze ions.\n\n[[File:LuckySurvivor.jpg|thumb|right|300 px|In the lucky survivor model, positive ions can be formed from highly charged clusters produced during break-up of the matrix- and analyte-containing solid.]]\nThe lucky survivor model (cluster ionization mechanism<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\" />) postulates that analyte molecules are incorporated in the matrix maintaining the charge state from solution.<ref name=\"KarasGl\u00fcckmann2000\">{{cite journal|last1=Karas|first1=Michael|last2=Gl\u00fcckmann|first2=Matthias|last3=Sch\u00e4fer|first3=J\u00fcrgen|title=Ionization in matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization: singly charged molecular ions are the lucky survivors|journal=Journal of Mass Spectrometry|volume=35|issue=1|year=2000|pages=1\u201312|issn=1076-5174|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1096-9888(200001)35:1<1::AID-JMS904>3.0.CO;2-0|pmid=10633229|bibcode=2000JMSp...35....1K}}</ref><ref name=\"McEwenLarsen2015\">{{cite journal|last1=McEwen|first1=Charles N.|last2=Larsen|first2=Barbara S.|title=Fifty years of desorption ionization of nonvolatile compounds|journal=International Journal of Mass Spectrometry|volume=377|year=2015|pages=515\u2013531|issn=1387-3806|doi=10.1016/j.ijms.2014.07.018|bibcode=2015IJMSp.377..515M}}</ref> Ion formation occurs through charge separation upon fragmentation of laser ablated clusters.<ref name=\"KarasKr\u00fcger2003\"/> Ions that are not neutralized by recombination with [[photoelectron]]s or [[counter ion]]s are the so-called lucky survivors.\n\nThe thermal model postulates that the high temperature facilitates the proton transfer between matrix and analyte in melted matrix liquid.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Ionization Mechanism of Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization|journal=Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry|volume=8|pages=21\u201339|last=Lu|first=I.-Chung|last2=Lee|first2=Chuping|date=2015|language=|doi=10.1146/annurev-anchem-071114-040315|pmid=26132345|last3=Lee|first3=Yuan-Tseh|last4=Ni|first4=Chi-Kung|bibcode=2015ARAC....8...21L}}</ref> Ion-to-neutral ratio is an important parameter to justify the theoretical model, and the mistaken citation of ion-to-neutral ratio could result in an erroneous determination of the ionization mechanism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tsai|first=Ming-Tsang|last2=Lee|first2=Sheng|last3=Lu|first3=I-Chung|last4=Chu|first4=Kuan Yu|last5=Liang|first5=Chi-Wei|last6=Lee|first6=Chih Hao|last7=Lee|first7=Yuan T.|last8=Ni|first8=Chi-Kung|date=2013-05-15|title=Ion-to-neutral ratio of 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid in matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization|journal=Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry|language=en|volume=27|issue=9|pages=955\u2013963|doi=10.1002/rcm.6534|pmid=23592197|issn=1097-0231|bibcode=2013RCMS...27..955T}}</ref> The model quantitatively predicts the increase in total ion intensity as a function of the concentration and proton affinity of the analytes, and the ion-to-neutral ratio as a function of the laser fluences.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=I-Chung|last2=Lee|first2=Chuping|last3=Chen|first3=Hui-Yuan|last4=Lin|first4=Hou-Yu|last5=Hung|first5=Sheng-Wei|last6=Dyakov|first6=Yuri A.|last7=Hsu|first7=Kuo-Tung|last8=Liao|first8=Chih-Yu|last9=Lee|first9=Yin-Yu|date=2014|title=Ion Intensity and Thermal Proton Transfer in Ultraviolet Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|volume=118|issue=15|pages=4132\u20134139|doi=10.1021/jp5008076|pmid=24707818|issn=1520-6106}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=I.-Chung|last2=Chu|first2=Kuan Yu|last3=Lin|first3=Chih-Yuan|last4=Wu|first4=Shang-Yun|last5=Dyakov|first5=Yuri A.|last6=Chen|first6=Jien-Lian|last7=Gray-Weale|first7=Angus|last8=Lee|first8=Yuan-Tseh|last9=Ni|first9=Chi-Kung|date=2015|title=Ion-to-Neutral Ratios and Thermal Proton Transfer in Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|language=en|volume=26|issue=7|pages=1242\u20131251|doi=10.1007/s13361-015-1112-3|pmid=25851654|issn=1044-0305|bibcode=2015JASMS..26.1242L}}</ref> This model also suggests that metal ion adducts (e.g., [M+Na]<sup>+</sup> or [M+K]<sup>+</sup>) are mainly generated from the thermally induced dissolution of salt.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Chuping|last2=Lu|first2=I.-Chung|last3=Hsu|first3=Hsu Chen|last4=Lin|first4=Hou-Yu|last5=Liang|first5=Sheng-Ping|last6=Lee|first6=Yuan-Tseh|last7=Ni|first7=Chi-Kung|date=2016|title=Formation of Metal-Related Ions in Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|language=en|volume=27|issue=9|pages=1491\u20131498|doi=10.1007/s13361-016-1424-y|pmid=27306427|issn=1044-0305|bibcode=2016JASMS..27.1491L}}</ref>\n\nThe [[matrix-assisted ionization]] (MAI) method uses matrix preparation similar to MALDI but does not require laser ablation to produce analyte ions of volatile or nonvolatile compounds.<ref name=\"Trimpin2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Trimpin|first1=Sarah|title=\"Magic\" Ionization Mass Spectrometry|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|volume=27|issue=1|year=2015|pages=4\u201321|issn=1044-0305|doi=10.1007/s13361-015-1253-4|pmid=26486514|pmc=4686549|bibcode=2016JASMS..27....4T}}</ref>  Simply exposing the matrix with analyte to the vacuum of the mass spectrometer creates ions with nearly identical charge states to electrospray ionization.<ref name=\"Trimpin\">{{cite journal |author=Trimpin, S, Inutan, ED |title=Matrix Assisted Ionization in Vacuum, a Sensitive and Widely Applicable Ionization Method for Mass Spectrometry |journal=J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom.|volume=24 |issue=5 |pages=722\u2013732 |doi=10.1007/s13361-012-0571-z|pmid=23526166 |year=2013 |bibcode=2013JASMS..24..722T }}</ref> It is suggested that there are likely mechanistic commonality between this process and MALDI.<ref name=\"McEwenLarsen2015\" />\n\n== Applications ==\n\n=== Biochemistry ===\nIn [[proteomics]], MALDI is used for the rapid identification of proteins isolated by using [[gel electrophoresis]]: [[SDS-PAGE]], [[size exclusion chromatography]], affinity chromatography, strong/weak ion exchange, isotope coded protein labelling (ICPL), and [[two-dimensional gel electrophoresis]]. [[Peptide mass fingerprinting]] is the most popular analytical application of MALDI-TOF mass spectrometers. MALDI TOF/TOF mass spectrometers are used to reveal amino acid sequence of peptides using post-source decay or high energy [[collision-induced dissociation]] (further use see [[mass spectrometry]]).\n\nLoss of sialic acid has been identified in papers when DHB has been used as a matrix for MALDI MS analysis of glycosylated peptides. Using sinapinic acid, 4-HCCA and DHB as matrices, S. Martin studied loss of sialic acid in glycosylated peptides by metastable decay in MALDI/TOF in linear mode and reflector mode.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Huberty |first1=M. C. |last2=Vath |first2=J. E. |last3=Yu |first3=W. |last4=Martin |first4=S. A. |year=1993 |title=Site-specific carbohydrate identification in recombinant proteins using MALD-TOF MS |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=65 |issue=20 |pages=2791\u20132800 |doi=10.1021/ac00068a015 |pmid=8250262 }}</ref> A group at Shimadzu Corporation derivatized the sialic acid by an amidation reaction as a way to improve detection sensitivity<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sekiya |first1=S. |last2=Wada |first2=Y. |last3=Tanaka |first3=K. |year=2005 |title=Derivatization for Stabilizing Sialic Acids in MALDI-MS |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=77 |issue=15 |pages=4962\u20134968 |doi=10.1021/ac050287o |pmid=16053310 }}</ref> and also demonstrated that ionic liquid matrix reduces a loss of sialic acid during MALDI/TOF MS analysis of sialylated oligosaccharides.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fukuyama |first1=Y. |last2=Nakaya |first2=S. |last3=Yamazaki |first3=Y. |last4=Tanaka |first4=K. |year=2008 |title=Ionic Liquid Matrixes Optimized for MALDI-MS of Sulfated/Sialylated/Neutral Oligosaccharides and Glycopeptides |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=80 |issue=6 |pages=2171\u20132179 |doi=10.1021/ac7021986 |pmid=18275166 }}</ref> THAP,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Papac |first1=D. I. |last2=Wong |first2=A. |last3=Jones |first3=A. J. S. |year=1996 |title=Analysis of Acidic Oligosaccharides and Glycopeptides by Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=68 |issue=18 |pages=3215\u20133223 |doi=10.1021/ac960324z |pmid=8797382 }}</ref> DHAP,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Harvey |first1=D. J. |year=1999 |title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry of carbohydrates |journal=[[Mass Spectrometry Reviews]] |volume=18 |issue=6 |pages=349\u2013451 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2787(1999)18:6<349::AID-MAS1>3.0.CO;2-H |bibcode=1999MSRv...18..349H |citeseerx=10.1.1.1012.1931 }}</ref> and a mixture of 2-aza-2-thiothymine and phenylhydrazine<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lattova |first1=E. |last2=Chen |first2=V. C. |last3=Varma |first3=S. |last4=Bezabeh |first4=T. |last5=Perreault |first5=H. |year=2007 |title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization on-target method for the investigation of oligosaccharides and glycosylation sites in glycopeptides and glycoproteins |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=21 |issue=10 |pages=1644\u20131650 |doi=10.1002/rcm.3007 |pmid=17465012 |bibcode=2007RCMS...21.1644L }}</ref> have been identified as matrices that could be used to minimize loss of sialic acid during MALDI MS analysis of glycosylated peptides.\n\nIt has been reported that a reduction in loss of some post-translational modifications can be accomplished if IR MALDI is used instead of UV MALDI<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tajiri |first1=M. |last2=Takeuchi |first2=T. |last3=Wada |first3=Y. |year=2009 |title=Distinct Features of Matrix-Assisted 6&nbsp;\u03bcm Infrared Laser Desorption/Ionization Mass Spectrometry in Biomolecular Analysis |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=81 |issue=16 |pages=6750\u20136755 |doi=10.1021/ac900695q |pmid=19627133 }}</ref>\n\nIn molecular biology, a mixture of [[5-methoxysalicylic acid]] and [[spermine]] can be used as a matrix for [[oligonucleotide]]s analysis in MALDI mass spectrometry,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Distler |first1=A. M. |last2=Allison |first2=J. |year=2001 |title=5-Methoxysalicylic acid and spermine: A new matrix for the matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization mass spectrometry analysis of oligonucleotides |journal=[[Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=12 |issue=4 |pages=456\u201362 |doi=10.1016/S1044-0305(01)00212-4 |pmid=11322192 }}</ref> for instance after [[oligonucleotide synthesis]].\n\n===Organic chemistry===\nSome synthetic macromolecules, such as [[catenane]]s and [[rotaxane]]s, [[dendrimer]]s and [[hyperbranched polymer]]s, and other assemblies, have molecular weights extending into the thousands or tens of thousands, where most ionization techniques have difficulty producing molecular ions. MALDI is a simple and fast analytical method that can allow chemists to rapidly analyze the results of such syntheses and verify their results.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n===Polymers===\nIn polymer chemistry MALDI can be used to determine the [[molar mass distribution]].<ref name=\"isbn3-540-44259-6\">{{cite book |last1=Schrepp |first1=W. |last2=Pasch |first2=H. |year=2003 |title=MALDI-TOF Mass Spectrometry of Synthetic Polymers |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |isbn=978-3-540-44259-2 }}</ref> Polymers with [[polydispersity]] greater than 1.2 are difficult to characterize with MALDI due to the signal intensity discrimination against higher mass oligomers.<ref name=Nielen1997>{{Cite journal |last1=Nielen |first1=M. W. F. |last2=Malucha |first2=S. |year=1997 |title=Characterization of polydisperse synthetic polymers by size-exclusion chromatography/matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry |journal=[[Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry]] |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=1194\u20131204 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-0231(199707)11:11<1194::AID-RCM935>3.0.CO;2-L |bibcode=1997RCMS...11.1194N }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9666717\">{{cite journal |last1=Wu |first1=K. J. |last2=Odom |first2=R. W. |year=1998 |title=Characterizing synthetic polymers by MALDI MS |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=70 |issue=13 |pages=456A\u2013461A |pmid=9666717 |doi=10.1021/ac981910q }}</ref><ref name=Schriemer1997>{{Cite journal |last1=Schriemer |first1=D. C. |last2=Li |first2=L. |year=1997 |title=Mass Discrimination in the Analysis of Polydisperse Polymers by MALDI Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry. 2. Instrumental Issues |journal=[[Analytical Chemistry (journal)|Analytical Chemistry]] |volume=69 |issue=20 |pages=4176\u20134183 |doi=10.1021/ac9707794 }}</ref>\n\nA good matrix for polymers is [[dithranol]]<ref name=\"SchaibergerMoss2008\">{{cite journal|last1=Schaiberger|first1=Audrey M.|last2=Moss|first2=Jason A.|title=Optimized sample preparation for MALDI mass spectrometry analysis of protected synthetic peptides|journal=Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry|volume=19|issue=4|year=2008|pages=614\u2013619|issn=1044-0305|doi=10.1016/j.jasms.2008.01.010|pmid=18295503}}</ref> or [[silver trifluoroacetate|AgTFA]].<ref name=\"BahrDeppe1992\">{{cite journal|last1=Bahr|first1=Ute.|last2=Deppe|first2=Andreas.|last3=Karas|first3=Michael.|last4=Hillenkamp|first4=Franz.|last5=Giessmann|first5=Ulrich.|title=Mass spectrometry of synthetic polymers by UV-matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=64|issue=22|year=1992|pages=2866\u20132869|issn=0003-2700|doi=10.1021/ac00046a036}}</ref> The sample must first be mixed with dithranol and the AgTFA added afterwards; otherwise the sample would precipitate out of solution.\n\n===Microbiology===\nMALDI/TOF spectra are used for the identification of micro-organisms such as bacteria or fungi. A portion of a colony of the microbe in question is placed onto the sample target and overlaid with matrix. The mass spectra generated are analyzed by dedicated software and compared with stored profiles. Species diagnosis by this procedure is much faster, more accurate and cheaper than other procedures based on immunological or biochemical tests. MALDI/TOF is becoming a standard method for species identification in medical microbiological laboratories.<ref name=\"pmid19583519\">{{cite journal |last1=Seng |first1=P. |last2=Drancourt |first2=M. |last3=Gouriet |first3=F. |last4=La Scola |first4=B. |last5=Fournier |first5=P. E. |last6=Rolain |first6=J. M. |last7=Raoult |first7=D. |title=Ongoing revolution in bacteriology: routine identification of bacteria by matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry |journal=[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=552\u20133 |year=2009 |pmid=19583519 |doi=10.1086/600885 }}</ref><ref name=\"SandrinGoldstein2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Sandrin|first1=Todd R.|last2=Goldstein|first2=Jason E.|last3=Schumaker|first3=Stephanie|title=MALDI TOF MS profiling of bacteria at the strain level: A review|journal=Mass Spectrometry Reviews|volume=32|issue=3|year=2013|pages=188\u2013217|issn=0277-7037|doi=10.1002/mas.21359|pmid=22996584|bibcode=2013MSRv...32..188S}}</ref>\n\nOne main advantage over other microbiological identification methods is its ability to rapidly and reliably identify, at low cost, a wide variety of microorganisms directly from the selective medium used to isolate them. The absence of the need to purify the suspect or \"presumptive\" colony<ref>{{Cite book|title = Molecular Microbial Diagnostic Methods - Pathways to Implementation for the Food and Water Industries|last = Capocefalo M., Ridley E. V., Tranfield E. Y. & Thompson K. C.|publisher = Elsevier|year = 2015|isbn = 978-0-12-416999-9|location = |pages = |chapter = Ch. 9 - MALDI-TOF: A rapid microbiological confirmation technique for food and water analysis|editor1=Cook N. |editor2=D'Agostino M. |editor3=Thompson K. C. }}</ref> allows for a much faster turn-around times.\n\nAnother advantage is the potential to predict [[antibiotic susceptibility]] of bacteria. A single mass spectral peak can predict methicillin resistance of ''Staphylococcus aureus'' <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rhoads | first1 = DD | year = 2016 | title = The presence of a single MALDI-TOF mass spectral peak predicts methicillin resistance in staphylococci. ''et al.'' | url = | journal = Diagn Microbiol Infect Dis | volume = 86 | issue = | page = 257 | doi = 10.1016/j.diagmicrobio.2016.08.001 | pmid = 27568365 }}</ref> MALDI can also detect [[carbapenemase]] of [[carbapenem-resistant enterobacteriaceae]],<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vogne | first1 = C. | display-authors = etal | year = 2014 | title = \"A simple, robust and rapid approach to detect carbapenemases in Gram-negative isolates by MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry \" validation with triple quadripole tandem mass spectrometry, microarray and PCR | url = | journal = Clin Microbiol Infect | volume = 20 | issue = | pages = O1106-12| doi = 10.1111/1469-0691 | pmid = 24930405 }}</ref> including ''[[Acinetobacter baumannii]]'' <ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 28303824 | doi=10.4103/0255-0857.202335 | volume=35 | title=Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionisation time-of-flight mass spectrometry rapid detection of carbapenamase activity in ''Acinetobacter baumannii'' isolates | year=2017 | journal=Indian J Med Microbiol | pages=85\u201389 | last1 = Abouseada | first1 = N | last2 = Raouf | first2 = M | last3 = El-Attar | first3 = E | last4 = Moez | first4 = P}}</ref> and ''[[Klebsiella pneumoniae]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sakarikou | first1 = C | last2 = Ciotti | first2 = M | last3 = Dolfa | first3 = C | last4 = Angeletti | first4 = S | last5 = Favalli | first5 = C | year = 2017 | title = Rapid detection of carbapenemase-producing Klebsiella pneumoniae strains derived from blood cultures by Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization-Time of Flight Mass Spectrometry (MALDI-TOF MS) | journal = BMC Microbiol | volume = 17 | issue = 1| page = 54 | doi = 10.1186/s12866-017-0952-3 | pmid = 28274205 | pmc = 5343375 }}</ref>\nHowever, most proteins that mediate antibiotic resistance are larger than MALDI-TOF's 2000-20,000 Da range for protein peak interpretation and only occasionally, as in the 2011 KPC outbreak at the NIH, a correlation between a peak and resistance conferring protein can be made.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lau | first1 = A. | display-authors = etal | date = August 2014 | title = A Rapid Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization\u2013Time of Flight Mass Spectrometry-Based Method for Single-Plasmid Tracking in an Outbreak of Carbapenem-Resistant Enterobacteriaceae | url = | journal = Journal of Clinical Microbiology | volume = 52 | issue = 8| pages = 2804\u20132812 | doi = 10.1128/JCM.00694-14 | pmid = 4136129 }}</ref>\n\n===Parasitology===\nMALDI/TOF spectra have been used for the detection and identification of various parasites such as [[trypanosomatid]]s,<ref name=\"AvilaAlmeida2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Avila|first1=C. C.|last2=Almeida|first2=F. G.|last3=Palmisano|first3=G.|title=Direct identification of trypanosomatids by matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization-time of flight mass spectrometry (DIT MALDI-TOF MS)|journal=Journal of Mass Spectrometry|volume=51|issue=8|year=2016|pages=549\u2013557|issn=1076-5174|doi=10.1002/jms.3763|pmid=27659938|bibcode=2016JMSp...51..549A}}</ref> ''[[Leishmania]]'' <ref name=\"LachaudFern\u00e1ndez-Ar\u00e9valo2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Lachaud|first1=Laurence|last2=Fern\u00e1ndez-Ar\u00e9valo|first2=Anna|last3=Normand|first3=Anne-C\u00e9cile|last4=Lami|first4=Patrick|last5=Nabet|first5=C\u00e9cile|last6=Donnadieu|first6=Jean Luc|last7=Piarroux|first7=Martine|last8=Djenad|first8=Farid|last9=Cassagne|first9=Carole|last10=Ravel|first10=Christophe|last11=Tebar|first11=Silvia|last12=Llovet|first12=Teresa|last13=Blanchet|first13=Denis|last14=Demar|first14=Magalie|last15=Harrat|first15=Zoubir|last16=Aoun|first16=Karim|last17=Bastien|first17=Patrick|last18=Mu\u00f1oz|first18=Carmen|last19=G\u00e1llego|first19=Montserrat|last20=Piarroux|first20=Renaud|last21=Loeffelholz|first21=Michael J.|title=Identification of ''Leishmania'' by Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization\u2013Time of Flight (MALDI-TOF) Mass Spectrometry Using a Free Web-Based Application and a Dedicated Mass-Spectral Library|journal=Journal of Clinical Microbiology|volume=55|issue=10|year=2017|pages=2924\u20132933|issn=0095-1137|doi=10.1128/JCM.00845-17|pmid=28724559|pmc=5625378}}</ref> and ''[[Plasmodium]]''.<ref name=\"LarocheAlmeras2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Laroche|first1=Maureen|last2=Almeras|first2=Lionel|last3=Pecchi|first3=Emilie|last4=Bechah|first4=Yassina|last5=Raoult|first5=Didier|last6=Viola|first6=Ang\u00e8le|last7=Parola|first7=Philippe|title=MALDI-TOF MS as an innovative tool for detection of ''Plasmodium'' parasites in ''Anopheles'' mosquitoes|journal=Malaria Journal|volume=16|issue=1|pages=5|year=2017|issn=1475-2875|doi=10.1186/s12936-016-1657-z|pmid=28049524|pmc=5209920}}</ref>\nIn addition to these [[unicellular]] parasites, MALDI/TOF can be used for the identification of [[cercariae]], the free-swimming stage of [[trematode]]s.<ref name=\"HugueninDepaquit2019\">{{cite journal|last1=Huguenin|first1=Antoine|last2=Depaquit|first2=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|last3=Villena|first3=Isabelle|last4=Fert\u00e9|first4=Hubert|title=MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry: a new tool for rapid identification of cercariae (Trematoda, Digenea)|journal=Parasite|volume=26|year=2019|pages=11|issn=1776-1042|doi=10.1051/parasite/2019011|url=https://www.parasite-journal.org/articles/parasite/full_html/2019/01/parasite180154/parasite180154.html|pmid= 30838972| pmc=6402365 }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\nMALDI/TOF spectra are often utilized in tandem with other analysis and spectroscopy techniques in the diagnosis of diseases. MALDI/TOF is a diagnostic tool with much potential because it allows for the rapid identification of proteins and changes to proteins without the cost or computing power of [[Next-generation sequencing|sequencing]] nor the skill or time needed to solve a crystal structure in [[X-ray crystallography]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nOne example of this is [[necrotizing enterocolitis]] (NEC), which is a devastating disease that affects the bowels of premature infants. The symptoms of NEC are very similar to those of [[sepsis]], and many infants die awaiting diagnosis and treatment. MALDI/TOF was used to quickly analyze fecal samples and find differences between the mutant and the functional protein responsible for NEC. There is hope that a similar technique could be used as a quick, diagnostic tool that would not require sequencing.<ref>Sim, K.; Shaw, A. G.; Randell, P.; Cox, M. J.; McClure, Z. E.; Li, M. S.; Haddad, M.; Langford, P. R.; Cookson, W. O.; Moffatt, M. F.; Kroll, J. S. Dysbiosis anticipating necrotizing enterocolitis in very premature infants. Clin. Infect. Dis. 2014.</ref>\n\nAnother example of the diagnostic power of MALDI/TOF is in the area of [[cancer]]. [[Pancreatic cancer]] remains one of the most deadly and difficult to diagnose cancers.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grantzdorffer | first1 = I | last2 = Carl-McGrath | first2 = S | last3 = Ebert | first3 = MP | last4 = Rocken | first4 = C | year = 2008 | title = Proteomics of pancreatic cancer | url = | journal = Pancreas | volume = 36 | issue = 4| pages = 329\u201336 | doi = 10.1097/MPA.0b013e31815cc452 }}</ref> Impaired [[cellular signaling]] due to mutations in membrane proteins has been long suspected to contribute to pancreatic cancer.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dhillon | first1 = AS | last2 = Hagan | first2 = S | last3 = Rath | first3 = O | last4 = Kolch | first4 = W | year = 2007 | title = MAP kinase signalling pathways in cancer | url = | journal = Oncogene | volume = 26 | issue = 22| pages = 3279\u201390 | doi = 10.1038/sj.onc.1210421 }}</ref> MALDI/TOF has been used to identify a [[membrane protein]] associated with pancreatic cancer and at one point may even serve as an early detection technique.<ref>Zhong, N.; Cui, Y.; Zhou, X.; Li, T.; Han, J. Identification of prohibitin 1 as a potential prognostic biomarker in human pancreatic carcinoma using modified aqueous two-phase partition system combined with 2D-MALDI-TOF-TOF-MS/MS. Tumour Biol. 2014.</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2017}}\n\nMALDI/TOF can also potentially be used to dictate treatment as well as diagnosis. MALDI/TOF serves as a method for determining the [[drug resistance]] of bacteria, especially to [[Beta-lactam antibiotic|\u03b2-lactams]] (Penicillin family). The MALDI/TOF detects the presence of carbapenemases, which indicates drug resistance to standard antibiotics. It is predicted that this could serve as a method for identifying a bacterium as drug resistant in as little as three hours. This technique could help physicians decide whether to prescribe more aggressive antibiotics initially.<ref>Hrab\u00e1k, Jaroslav (2015). \"Detection of Carbapenemases Using Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionization Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry (MALDI-TOF MS) Meropenem Hydrolysis Assay\". Methods in Molecular Biology (1064-3745), 1237, p. 91.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Peptide mass fingerprinting]]\n* [[PEGylation]]\n* [[MALDI imaging]]\n*[[Matrix (mass spectrometry)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Ragoussis |first1=J. |last2=Elvidge |first2=G. P. |last3=Kaur |first3=K. |last4=Colella |first4=S. |year=2006 |title=Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption/Ionisation, Time-of-Flight Mass Spectrometry in Genomics Research |journal=[[PLoS Genetics]] |volume=2 |issue=7 |pages=e100 |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.0020100 |pmc=1523240 |pmid=16895448 }} \n*{{cite journal |last1=Hardouin |first1=J. |year=2007 |title=Protein sequence information by matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization in-source decay mass spectrometry |journal=[[Mass Spectrometry Reviews]] |volume=26 |issue=5 |pages=672\u201382 |doi=10.1002/mas.20142 |pmid=17492750 |bibcode=2007MSRv...26..672H }} \n*{{cite book |last1=Peter-Katalinic |first1=J. |last2=Hillenkamp |first2=F. |year=2007 |title=MALDI MS: A Practical Guide to Instrumentation, Methods and Applications |publisher=[[Wiley-VCH]] |isbn=978-3-527-31440-9 }} \n*{{cite book |last1=Schrepp |first1=W. |last2=Pasch |first2=H. |year=2003 |title=MALDI-TOF Mass Spectrometry of Synthetic Polymers |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |isbn=978-3-540-44259-2 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091102022351/http://www.magnet.fsu.edu/education/tutorials/tools/ionization_maldi.html Primer on Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization (MALDI)] National High Magnetic Field Laboratory\n\n{{Mass spectrometry}}\n{{lasers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization}}\n[[Category:Ion source]]\n[[Category:Biochemistry methods]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMatrix:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix-assisted_laser_desorption/ionization"}
{"title_page": "A151 road", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{cleanup HTML|date=August 2019|tags=cite}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=151\n|map=A151 road map.jpg\n|map_notes=Click map to enlarge\n|length_mi=\n|direction_a= \n|terminus_a = [[Colsterworth]]\n|direction_b= \n|terminus_b = [[Holbeach]]\n|junction   = {{jct|country=GBR|A|1|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|6121|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|15|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|16|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|17|noshield1=|nolink1= }}\n|destinations= \n}}\n\nThe '''A151 road''' is relatively minor part of the British road system. It lies entirely in the [[county]] of [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]].  Its western end lies at coordinates {{coord|52|48.1892|N|0|36.5179|W|region:GB|display=inline|format=dms|name=A151 road, western end}} otherwise, {{gbmapping|SK938238}}.<sup id=\"fn_1_back\">[[#fn 1|1]]</sup> This article attempts to deal with its several aspects by treating some separately, before integrating them with the others into an overall picture, sequentially from its western end.\n\n==The British Road Numbering System==\nIn Britain, roads of greater and medium importance are numbered according to a system in which the smaller number of digits indicates a more major route.  The [[motorway]]s are prefixed by M and the principal other roads by the letter A.  The roads [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] to [[A6 road (Great Britain)|A6]] radiate from [[London]] with A1 as the axial route of the country, running between London and [[Edinburgh]]. Roads with numbers beginning with 1 lie to the east of the A1, clockwise when viewed on a map. The details are explained under [[Great Britain road numbering scheme]].\n\n==The A151: Summary==\nIn the early 19th century, the A151 would have been called a cross-road<sup id=\"fn_2_back\">[[#fn 2|2]]</sup> since it runs across the pattern of these radial routes. As originally designated, it ran from the A15 at Bourne Market Place (TF095201), eastwards to Fleet Hargate, three kilometres east of Holbeach (TF393250), on the A17.  Its present western section, between Colsterworth and Bourne, was part of the B676 road.<sup id=\"fn_3_back\">[[#fn 3|3]]</sup>\n\nRoad building and re-thinking of the road system have meant that nowadays, its western end is on the A1 near [[Woolsthorpe by Colsterworth|Colsterworth]], in the administrative district of [[South Kesteven]],<sup id=\"fn_4_back\">[[#fn 4|4]]</sup> and its eastern end on the A17 near [[Holbeach]], in the district of [[South Holland, England|South Holland]].<sup id=\"fn_5_back\">[[#fn 5|5]]</sup> On the way, it passes to the north of [[Grimsthorpe Castle]] and at TF076200, just to the south of [[Bourne Woods|Bourne Wood]]. Then at TF095201, it bisects [[Bourne, Lincolnshire|Bourne]]. It enters [[The Fens]] on the eastern edge of that small town. At TF154207, it passes through the hamlet of [[Twenty, Lincolnshire|Twenty]], in Bourne North Fen. At [[Guthram Gowt]], it leaves [[Kesteven]] by crossing the [[South Forty-Foot Drain]] into [[Holland, England|Holland]]. The principal town of South Holland is [[Spalding, Lincolnshire|Spalding]] (TF245227), which is also the main town on the A151 route. Across the [[River Welland]], lie [[Moulton, Lincolnshire|Moulton]], then Holbeach, near which the A151 ends at the A17 (TF350258). That road leads on to [[King's Lynn]] and [[East Anglia]].\n\n==Turnpike roads==\nAs elsewhere, roads in England have developed over many years.  Perhaps some of the A151 lies on lines which are pre-Roman. In other words, parts are two thousand or more years old. However, change is constant and little of the road is that old.  In the nature of things, these changes are poorly or not at all documented, so will be treated generally, in that light, in an overview below. The historical part of the story begins with the [[turnpike trust|turnpike roads]].\n\nThe A151 was originally designated such in 1921.  Then, the roads were much as they had been forty or fifty years before, under the turnpike trusts.  Since the [[World War II|Second World War]], there has been much building of by-passes and the like so that the precise lines have sometimes changed but they are still fundamentally the same. The main difference in the present case is that the road designation has been extended from the A15 at Bourne to the A1 at Colsterworth, while at the other end, the easternmost three kilometres have been replaced by a new part of the A17.\n\nIn the field of [[Act of Parliament|acts of Parliament]] founding turnpike trusts, much was happening locally in 1756. The Wansford to [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]] trust on the [[Great North Road (United Kingdom)|Great North Road]] had been set up in 1749 but in 1756, its sphere was extended through Stamford to Bourne.  The last 1.6 kilometres of this road, as the trust left it, running down the hill to Bourne Market Place, are now part of the A151. It was freed from tolls on 1 November 1871. The half of this section which lies outside the modern town was probably built by the trust between 1756 and the [[Enclosure Acts|Bourne Enclosure Awards]] of 1770\u20131.<sup id=\"fn_6_back\">[[#fn 6|6]]</sup>\n\nThe Lincoln Heath to [[Peterborough]] Trust was also established in 1756. Its remit included the forerunner of the present A15 which crosses the end of the Stamford road at Bourne Market Place. However, also included with this was the road from the Stamford road west of Bourne (a place known locally as Stamford Hill),<sup id=\"fn_7_back\">[[#fn 7|7]]</sup> to Colsterworth. With the exception of the western extremity, in Colsterworth village, this is now part of the A151. It was freed from tolls on 1 November 1882.\n\nThe Lincoln Heath to Peterborough trust was organized in districts of which that covering the road from Colsterworth to Stamford Hill, Bourne was the \u2018\u2019West District\u2019\u2019.  In 1860, it was re-grouped with the \u2018\u2019Middle District\u2019\u2019 which extended from Graby Bar (TF091295) to [[Market Deeping]] (TF138099).<sup id=\"fn_8_back\">[[#fn 8|8]]</sup>\n\nFrom Spalding, through Holbeach to Long Sutton, beyond the end of the modern A151, the road was turnpiked in 1764.<sup id=\"fn_9_back\">[[#fn 9|9]]</sup> It was freed from tolls on 1 November 1866.  It may not be coincidental that this was the year of the final opening of the [[railway]] from Bourne to King's Lynn, the line having been opened in stages from 1858. This road was declared a main road by the Highways Act of 1878.\n\nThe road from Bourne to Spalding was turnpiked in 1822 and freed from tolls in 1860. It was declared a main road by the Highways Act of 1878. Before 1822, this section was in three parts. One led out from Bourne onto Bourne North Fen. The Spalding end led out from Spalding to the Spalding and Pinchbeck fen edge bank. The linking section was not officially a road. There was however, some [[Drover (Britain)|droving]] traffic which was frowned upon by the drainage authorities, whose embankments it tended to erode. According to Cary's map of 1787, the official route ran ''via'' Tongue End (TF155188) and crossed the [[River Glen, Lincolnshire|River Glen]] at Gurthram (TF173224).\n\n===Toll gates===\nThe principal source of information about the positions of toll gates is the [[Ordnance Survey]] 1 inch map published in 1824.<sup id=\"fn_5a_back\">[[#fn 5a|5a]]</sup> It places them as follows: <!-- frustratingly the online OS maps are all just after the turnpike trusts had wound themselves up -->\n\n* Corby Toll Bar. SK969234 (also 1834-6)\n* T[urn] P[ike]. SK991247\n* T P. TF062210 (also 1834-6)\n* T P. TF079198 (also 1834-6 but there shown as on the Stamford road)\n* Friers Bar. TF117206 (Exeter Estate book but no gate shown.)\n* T P. TF169223 (corroborated by Paterson's Roads)  (also 1834-6)\n* T P. TF198244 (corroborated by Paterson's Roads)  (also 1834-6)\n* T P. TF2724. (also 1834-6 and the O.S. map of 1890 shows \"The Gate\" [[public house]]).<sup id=\"fn_5b_back\">[[#fn 5b|5b]]</sup>\n* T P. TF466217. (also 1834-6)\n\nThe six digit National grid References of the marked positions on the 1824 map are taken from an equivalent modern map. The four digit references <!-- what four digit refs? --> are much less accurate, being taken from an Ordnance Survey map by inspection of Wright Fig.3. The Ordnance Survey does not note the Friars Bar toll gate but in the Exeter Estate book,{{ref|16}} the position is called Friers Bar though no obstruction of the road by a gate is indicated.  ''[[Paterson's Roads]]'' is a road book listing the features of roads and mileages from the ends of its itineraries, sequentially.\n\nIt is noticeable and a little surprising that according to the Ordnance Survey, it was possible in some cases to go a long way out of a town before coming to a toll gate. This is particularly noticeable eastwards from Spalding.\n\n===The Condition of the turnpike roads===\nWe have a few references to the condition of parts of the turnpike forerunners of the A151. Arthur Young's book on the Lincolnshire economy<sup id=\"fn_(50)_back\">[[#fn (50)|(50)]]</sup>  was published in 1813, while the first Fosdyke bridge was still under construction. He therefore, will have taken the future A151 between Spalding and Fleet Hargate on his journey from [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]] to [[Wisbech]]. He wrote of it thus: ''In the Hundred of Skirbeck to Boston, and thence to Wisbeach, [turnpike roads] are generally made with [[silt]], or old sea-sand, deposited under various parts of the country ages ago, and when moderately wet are very good; but dreadfully dusty and heavy in dry weather; and also on a thaw they are like mortar. Take the [[county]] in general, and they must be esteemed below par.'' What he is saying is that the turnpike roads in the Townlands were made of the same marine silt as forms the land itself in that part of the country.  The heaviness in dry weather to which he refers, arose from the loose, deep, sandy surface through which wheels would have to be dragged.\nAccording to Wheeler, {{convert|1|LT}} of silt was reckoned to cover {{convert|1|yd}} in a length of a road, {{convert|18|in|mm}} thick and {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide, the silt costing about 8d. to 10d. per ton for digging and spreading. In some cases the road was turned over. That is a pit was dug in the road until the silt was reached then that was dug out and formed into the carriageway. The surface of the next length was dug and put into the pit as a foundation then the silt dug and placed on top of it and so on along the road.\nGravel was used where obtainable and from about 1870, Wheeler introduced [[granite]].  By the end of the 20th century granite and [[slag]] were being consolidated by [[steamroller|steam roller]]<ref>Wheeler. pp 441\u2013445.</ref> Of the Bourne to Colsterworth road, Young said ''we were every moment either buried in quagmires of mud or racked to dislocation over pieces of rock which they term mending.'' Materials and methods for repairing fenland roads are described by Wheeler. The best material available was dug locally from pits.\n\n==The Terrain==\nWhen roads are built by engineers with capital to support their work, they are successfully able to build roads across difficult soils.  Modern road builders have less need to seek out easy geological conditions. When roads were made not by [[civil engineers]] but by people walking on the ground, the road followed the [[soils]] which were found to be easiest under foot.\nThe A151 passes across two types of country, the upland and the fen. The highest point on it lies within a kilometre of its western end at 123 metres above [[mean sea level]]. It then passes across a gently sloping dissected plateau of [[Jurassic]] rocks capped in its highest parts by glacial clay. After about 16 kilometres, it enters the fen and is soon at about two metres, rising to three, nearer the coast.\n\n==Description==\n\n===The Western End===\nHaving for some time, extended its influence by diplomacy and trade,<sup id=\"fn_5_back\">[[#fn 5|5]]</sup> The [[Roman Empire]] began to take control in [[Roman Britain|Britain]] from the year 43. An important part of the means of control was the building of soundly-built roads, running directly between key places.<sup id=\"fn_(6)_back\">[[#fn (6)|(6)]]</sup> This led the engineers to overcome all but the greatest obstacles rather than going round them. One result of this was that they built roads on soils which others would have avoided. When the Roman authorities had withdrawn from Britain and their roads wore out, people began to wander from the [[Roman road]] lines where they could find a more secure footing by taking another line.<sup id=\"fn_(7)_back\">[[#fn (7)|(7)]]</sup>\n\nThe Roman equivalent of the A1 was built to a very high standard, during the early years of Roman rule in Britain. The [[English people|English]] successors of the Romans in Britain, called this road [[Ermine Street]] from their word for \"soldier\", compare the [[German language|German]] personal name, Herman.<sup id=\"fn_(8a)_back\">[[#fn (8a)|(8a)]]</sup> The twenty kilometre length of Ermine Street, at roughly the centre of which, the line of the A151 lies, passed over chalky till (boulder clay) which is very sticky when wet. As the Ermine Street carriageway broke up, people sought easier going by moving down towards the small [[River Witham]] whose valley had been eroded through the till, into the [[Jurassic]] [[limestone]] below it.\n\nThus, in 1756 when the Colsterworth to Bourne road was [[Toll road|turnpiked]],<sup id=\"fn_(9a)_back\">[[#fn (9a)|(9a)]]</sup> the toll road which was to become the A151  began at the crossroads in Colsterworth, further west than it now does, though the first toll gate noted by the 1824 Ordnance Survey map was about three kilometres from there. When the Colsterworth bypass was built, its southern half was placed virtually on the Ermine Street line so that now, while the A151 still begins at the A1, it is not at the old Great North Road but at Ermine Street, on the chalky till soil that we start our journey. Bourne Road, Colsterworth, the section removed from the A151, remains part of the B676, the road which leads westwards, towards [[Melton Mowbray]].<sup id=\"fn_(10)_back\">[[#fn (10)|(10)]]</sup>\n\nOnce the clutter associated with a trunk road junction is left behind, the road passes through agricultural land and woods. To the north are fairly level fields and to the south, [[Twyford Wood]], which cloaks the remains of [[RAF North Witham|North Witham airfield]].<sup id=\"fn_(11)_back\">[[#fn (11)|(11)]]</sup>\n\n===Corby Glen===\nAt the end of the wood, we leave Colsterworth parish. Three kilometres from the start, at the hamlet of Birkholme, the road finds a shallow valley formed by erosion which has cut through the till and exposed the underlying Jurassic limestone soils. Here, the 1824 map shows our first toll gate, Corby Toll Bar.<sup id=\"fn_(12)_back\">[[#fn (12)|(12)]]</sup> The road follows this valley, under the railway main line, past the second toll gate site at the junction with the Boothby Pagnel road (B1176), then down to the River Glen at [[Corby Glen]], where it turns a little southwards to avoid more glacial till and keep to the upper [[Lincolnshire limestone]].<sup id=\"fn_(13)_back\">[[#fn (13)|(13)]]</sup>\nThe land between Colsterworth and the western edge of Bourne is a plateau, gently sloping down to the east and much dissected by erosion during periods when it was near but not under ice caps. The River Glen which we crossed at Corby Glen is also called the West Glen and is in one of the two main dissecting valleys.<sup id=\"fn_(140)_back\">[[#fn (14)|(14)]]</sup>\nEast of Corby Glen, we are on a strip of un-dissected plateau. The surface dips very gently towards the east but the [[Stratum|geological strata]] dip more steeply so that a kilometre out of Corby Glen, the road passes onto the strata above the limestone, known as the [[Upper Estuarine Series]], the [[Blisworth Limestone]], [[Blisworth clay]], [[Cornbrash]] and [[Kellaways clay]], in that order.\n\n===Edenham===\nAt Irnham crossroads,<sup id=\"fn_(15)_back\">[[#fn (15)|(15)]]</sup> the A151 leaves Corby Glen parish for that of Edenham and is back down on the cornbrash. To the north, unseen in its little valley beyond the woods is Irnham, once the home of Sir Geoffrey Luttrell, who commissioned the [[Illuminated manuscript|Luttrell Psalter]],<sup id=\"fn_(16)_back\">[[#fn (16)|(16)]]</sup> a book which tells us so much of English everyday life in the 14th century.<sup id=\"fn_17_back\">[[#fn (17)|(17)]]</sup>\n\nThe road dips into the valley of the stream which flows on to form the lake in Grimsthorpe Park.  Just skirting the glacial till, it rises to the crest at the other side, on the Kellaways clay and sand and turns sharply left onto the till.  It used to go straight on and pass the north front of [[Grimsthorpe Castle]].  When the soil in the field beyond the bend is bare, its course can still be seen. The castle's owner did a deal with the turnpike trustees.  He brought land on the other side of the road into his park and built them a new, though longer road around it. Once the semi-circular diversion is completed, the road turns sharp left again, through Grimsthorpe where it is on Jurassic clay.  The 1824 [[Ordnance Survey]] map shows both the old and the new roads.\n\nAt Grimsthorpe village, the A151 is in the second of the main valleys dissecting the plateau, that of the East Glen river. From its association with Edenham, this river is often called the Eden.  The West and East Glens join near Wilsthorpe, at {{gbmapping|TF0913}}.  Through Grimsthorpe and Edenham, there are numerous bends and winds across the small exposures Jurassic soils, glacial gravel and alluvium, until the road climbs out of the valley over the till-capped ridge which separates Edenham parish from Bourne. On the glacial clay soil of the till, it passes between woods, including [[Bourne Woods|Bourne Wood]].<sup id=\"fn_(19)_back\">[[#fn (19)|(19)]]</sup>\n\n===Bourne===\nAs the road arrives back on the Jurassic clay, it meets the [[A6121 road|A6121]], a road designation which ends here, having begun at Morcott, {{gbmapping|SK926004}} in [[Rutland]], on the other side of the A1, hence its beginning with the digit 6. In 1824, there was a toll gate here.<sup id=\"fn_(20)_back\">[[#fn (20)|(20)]]</sup> The course of the A151 is directly down the slope into Bourne. It is clear archaeologically that the road used to run parallel with this and about 200 metres to the south. Historically, there appears to be no commonly available record as to when the move was made.  It was certainly in two stages. The move of the upper part was probably made in the 18th century; the lower, in about 1140, when Bourne castle was built across it. Its present course is dictated by the former presence of Bourne Castle at the town end and by a desire to keep to the crest of a slight ridge in the hillside.<sup id=\"fn_(21)_back\">[[#fn (21)|(21)]]</sup>\n\nIt is towards the top of this section that it is possible to detect a change in slope betraying the former presence of a shore of the [[Devensian]] [[periglacial]] lake, which was impounded by the ice into the Fenland basin. It was more evident but the declivity of the road has been smoothed out a little.<sup id=\"fn_(22)_back\">[[#fn (22)|(22)]]</sup>\n\nMuch more modern, is the bypass road which joins from the south at the entrance to the town and just below the level of the surface of the former lake. This opened for use on 8 October 2005. In the town, the A151 passes immediately outside the castle site, along the latter's northern edge. However the plots along this side of the road were first laid out for houses in around 1280, so that the castle is no longer casually apparent.<sup id=\"fn_(23)_back\">[[#fn (23)|(23)]]</sup>\n\nAt Bourne Market Place, the A151 crosses the A15. This road used to be part of the Lincoln Heath to Peterborough turnpike road, whose act of parliament is dated 1756.  It was this trust which, in 1820, demolished the old town hall which used to stand in the street here.\n\nAt the junction, the road to the north led directly form the main gate of the castle. The market place was positioned immediately across a moat and a [[pomoerium|pom\u0153rium]], outside the gate but those are no longer visible from the road. However, our road continues not straight ahead but on a 45\u00b0 angle toward the south. This bend arose because it passed around the perimeter of the pom\u0153rium until it met the road leading eastwards from the gate. As the A151 reaches this, it turns back through 45\u00b0 and continues eastwards along that approach road, across the line of the Roman version of the A15, [[King Street (Roman road)|King Street]] and past the [[Bourne Abbey|Abbey Lawn]]. This is now a picturesque [[cricket]] ground, but was an 18th-century sheep lawn.<sup id=\"fn_(24)_back\">[[#fn (24)|(24)]]</sup> Soon, the road leaves the 12th century, [[Norman dynasty|Norman]] road, heading towards the pre-Norman town. On arrival, it turns eastwards again, at the same time as crossing the now-buried course of the [[Car Dyke]] and onto the fen-edge gravel.  This is material which drifted down the slope which we have followed, while it was under the water of the Devensian periglacial lake.\n\nThe Car Dyke is generally taken as the boundary of The Fens, though here, it heralds the more commercial part of the town. At once, the road passes the former works of [[British Racing Motors|BRM]], the [[Formula One]] motor racing Constructors' Champion in 1962. The firm is gone but it has left an engineering tradition in the town. Shortly, the road turns north-eastwards, following the bank of the [[Bourne-Morton Canal|Roman artificial river]] across the fen, the Old Ea. At the edge of the town, it turns away from the now hidden river bed, almost eastwards across the black, [[humic]] soil of Bourne North Fen.<sup id=\"fn_(25)_back\">[[#fn (25)|(25)]]</sup> Here we begin to see The Fens as the region more typically is, a broad, nearly flat, agricultural land.\n\nAt {{gbmapping|TF118207}}, the road turns due eastwards at Friar Bar, where to judge by its name, at one stage was a toll bar. The Ordnance Survey does not note it but on the Exeter Estate book,<sup id=\"fn_(26)_back\">[[#fn (26)|(26)]]</sup> it is called Friers Bar.  The road from Bourne to Spalding had been turnpiked in 1822,<sup id=\"fn_(27)_back\">[[#fn (27)|(27)]]</sup> after the survey had begun. So it looks as though the Ordnance Survey had overlooked it. From here, the road runs 3\u00bd kilometres, straight to [[Twenty, Lincolnshire|Twenty]].\n\nThe Car Dyke marked the western boundary of the [[royal forest]] decreed, by one of the [[Norman dynasty|Norman]] kings. It extended south and east, across the fens to the Welland. There seems to be no precise agreement as to when the land was disafforested. It was somewhere between 1190 and 1230.<sup id=\"fn_(28)_back\">[[#fn (28)|(28)]]</sup> The obvious occasion was the signing of [[Magna Carta]] in 1215 or perhaps, on one of its re-issues. That document mentions [[John of England|King John's]] afforestations.\n\nRoads on the black soils tend to crumble at the edges as the soft humus collapses and oxidises. This road is typical of fen roads, in needing frequent attention to deal with that. It is typical too, in that it rises and falls as it passes over the silt banks left amongst the peat by small to medium marine creeks from the Middle [[Bronze Age]], 3 to 3\u00bd thousand years ago. This was before the peat in the soil was laid down.\n\nIn the black fens, the buildings are virtually always to be found on these old creeks, known as roddons. The many small roddons in Bourne North Fen merge at Twenty. There, the road uses part of this larger roddon by turning along it towards Guthram. Nowadays, this place is called Guthram Gowt but until the steam drainage engine was erected there, in 184?, it was Guthram Cote.\n\nIn the late medieval period, people lived on the fen edge and the Townlands but the fens themselves were thinly populated. There were however, a few comparatively grand establishments called Halls, Neslam Hall at {{gbmapping|TF1732}}, for example. It was a grange of [[Sempringham Priory]] on the site of the modern Mornington House round which the district boundary is still diverted as it was when the abbey, on the Kesteven fen edge, owned it. There were more but still rather few smaller dwellings called cotes. Moors Cote lay in Bourne North Fen, to the south-east of Twenty and Guthram Cote stood on the boundary between Kesteven and Holland{{ref|18}}, on an island of Devensian deposits, the Abbey sand and gravel. The road book, Paterson's Roads, of 1826, lists a toll gate at Guthram Cote, a distance of {{convert|5+1/4|mi}} from Bourne. Just to the east of this was the bridge over what it calls the [[South Forty-Foot Drain|South Forty-Foot Eau]](15).\n\n===Pinchbeck===\nThe Kesteven-Holland boundary is formed by the [[South Forty-Foot Drain]], the main land drain of the Black Sluice Level. The present layout of the drainage dates from the Act of Parliament of 1765 but this part of the South Forty-foot is a re-use of one of the main drains of the Lindsey Level, a scheme which was declared complete in 1638. On the other side, in Pinchbeck North Fen, the road begins to wind, something quite unusual in these fens. It was laid out on the bank of a [[soak dike]] called the Weir Dike, which was cut in about 1600. In Pinchbeck North Fen, the dike is now largely defunct. The instructions stipulated that it should be at a distance of 100 feet (33M) from the bank of the River Glen. As the river bank meandered a little, so the road does(13).\n\nThe river is the one the A151 crosses at Corby Glen and Edenham. Here the two parts are combined. Beyond the Glen, to the south, is an area of dense [[Romano-British]] occupation. On this side, a little is known but if there is more, it is covered with post-Roman marine silt(14). It looks as though this part of the river began as a single sea bank, keeping the tide out of Pinchbeck South Fen but allowing it into the lower part of that area behind the townland to the north of the road. In the late Roman or early post-Roman period, the Glen escaped from its artificial Roman course of which the Bourne Old Ea was part. (The road follows the bank of this while leaving Bourne) and found its way to these tidal flats. Later, at some early but unknown medieval date, the marsh was turned into a polder of sorts and the Glen was directed along the old sea bank which then became one of the river banks. Thus, the course of the road was determined ultimately, by that of the sea bank.\n\nThe River Glen will have been in the phase when it flowed into the tidal marsh, with its mouth at Guthram, at around 500, the time when the unknown writer who goes under the name of [[Nennius]] tells us that [[King Arthur]] fought his first battle against the English settlers at the mouth of the River Glein. See [[Historia Britonum]] numbered paragraph 3. See also [[Sites and places associated with Arthurian legend]].\n<!--\n===In the Townlands===\n-->\n\n==Footnotes==\n<!-- '''Links from grid references will leave you in limbo''' unless you are very careful.  '''Right''' click on the link and select '''Open in New Window''' then, under Great Britain, select '''Find this location''' in Find this location on the Ordnance Survey Get-a-map. It is possible to arrange the map window and the Wikipedia window to have both in view together. Unless you are making a serious study, these map links are best avoided.\n--> \n* <cite id=\"fn_1\">[[#fn 1 back|Note 1:]]</cite> This is a Bri