ent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTurnpike roads:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1770-1 \u2192 1770\u20131", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A151_road"}
{"title_page": "Dosoftei", "text_new": "{{Infobox saint\n|name=Dosoftei\n|birth_date=October 26, 1624\n|death_date=December 13, 1693\n|feast_day=December 13\n|venerated_in=October 14, 2005\n|image=Dosoftei.jpg\n|imagesize=200px\n|caption=Metropolitan Dosoftei\n|birth_place=[[Suceava]]\n|death_place=[[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Poland]]\n|canonized_date=July 2005\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=Synod of the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n}}\n\n'''Dimitrie Baril\u0103''' ({{IPA-ro|di\u02c8mitri.e ba\u02c8ril\u0259}}), better known under his [[Monk|monastical]] name '''Dosoftei''' ({{IPA-ro|dosof\u02c8tej|}}; October 26, 1624&mdash;December 13, 1693), was a [[Moldavia]]n [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]], scholar, poet and translator.\n\nBorn in [[Suceava]], he attended the school of the [[Trei Ierarhi Church|\"Trei Ierarhi\" Monastery]] of [[Ia\u015fi]] and then at the Orthodox Brotherhood school in [[Lviv]], where he studied [[humanities]] and learned several languages.\n\nIn 1648 he became a monk at [[Probota, Suceava|Probota]] Monastery, and was later [[bishop]] of [[Hu\u015fi]] (1658\u20131660) and [[Roman, Romania|Roman]] (1660\u20131671) to become [[Metropolitan of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan bishop of Moldavia]] (1671\u20131674 and again 1675-1686). In 1686 he moved to [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Poland]] where he stayed for the rest of his life.\n\n[[Image:CasaDosoftei.Iasi-Romania.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Dosoftei's residence in [[Ia\u015fi]]]]\nHe was one of the most important ethnic [[Romanians|Romanian]] scholars of the 17th century, the very first important [[Romanian language]] poet and the first translator into Romanian of epics, works on history, as well as religious scriptures Moldavia had. His most famous work is the Romanian [[psalter]] in [[Poetry|verse]].\n\nThe Synod of the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] [[Canonization|canonized]] Dosoftei in July 2005, a fact that was proclaimed on October 14, 2005. His feast day is December 13.\n\n==Works==\n* ''Dosofteiu Mitropolitul Moldovei 1671\u20131686. Psaltirea in versuri publicata de pe manuscrisul original \u0219i de pe edi\u021biunea dela 1673 de Prof. I. Bianu. Edi\u021biunea Academie\u012d Rom\u00e2ne.'' Bucuresci 1887 ([https://books.google.com/books?id=OmRtAAAAIAAJ Google] [https://books.google.com/books?id=Z24YAAAAYAAJ Google])\n\n==References==\n* \u0410\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u0424., \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442. \"\u041c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442 \u0421\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0414\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0444\u0435\u0439,\" ''\u0416\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0438'', 1974, No. 3, 50-52.\n* Mirela Cimpoi, [http://www.jurnalul.ro/articol_57316/dosoftei__sfantul_invatat.html \"Dosoftei, sf\u00e2ntul \u00eenv\u0103\u0163at\"], ''[[Jurnalul Na\u0163ional]]'', July 17, 2006\n{{Wikisourcelang|ro|Autor:Dosoftei|Dosoftei (works in Romanian)}}\n\n== Presence in English language anthologies ==\n\n* T''estament - 400 Years of Romanian Poetry - 400 de ani de poezie rom\u00e2neasc\u0103'' - billingual edition Romanian/English - [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and principal translator) with [[Daniel Reynaud]], Adriana Paul & Eva Foster - Editura Minerva, 2019 - {{ISBN|978-973-21-1070-6}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:17th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:1624 births]]\n[[Category:1693 deaths]]\n[[Category:Early Modern Romanian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Suceava]]\n[[Category:Romanian Orthodox metropolitan bishops]]\n[[Category:Romanian saints]]\n[[Category:17th-century Romanian people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox saint\n|name=Dosoftei\n|birth_date=October 26, 1624\n|death_date=December 13, 1693\n|feast_day=December 13\n|venerated_in=October 14, 2005\n|image=Dosoftei.jpg\n|imagesize=200px\n|caption=Metropolitan Dosoftei\n|birth_place=[[Suceava]]\n|death_place=[[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Poland]]\n|canonized_date=July 2005\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=Synod of the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n}}\n\n'''Dimitrie Baril\u0103''' ({{IPA-ro|di\u02c8mitri.e ba\u02c8ril\u0259}}), better known under his [[Monk|monastical]] name '''Dosoftei''' ({{IPA-ro|dosof\u02c8tej|}}; October 26, 1624&mdash;December 13, 1693), was a [[Moldavia]]n [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]], scholar, poet and translator.\n\nBorn in [[Suceava]], he attended the school of the [[Trei Ierarhi Church|\"Trei Ierarhi\" Monastery]] of [[Ia\u015fi]] and then at the Orthodox Brotherhood school in [[Lviv]], where he studied [[humanities]] and learned several languages.\n\nIn 1648 he became a monk at [[Probota, Suceava|Probota]] Monastery, and was later [[bishop]] of [[Hu\u015fi]] (1658\u20131660) and [[Roman, Romania|Roman]] (1660\u20131671) to become [[Metropolitan of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan bishop of Moldavia]] (1671\u20131674 and again 1675-1686). In 1686 he moved to [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Poland]] where he stayed for the rest of his life.\n\n[[Image:CasaDosoftei.Iasi-Romania.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Dosoftei's residence in [[Ia\u015fi]]]]\nHe was one of the most important ethnic [[Romanians|Romanian]] scholars of the 17th century, the very first important [[Romanian language]] poet and the first translator into Romanian of epics, works on history, as well as religious scriptures Moldavia had. His most famous work is the Romanian [[psalter]] in [[Poetry|verse]].\n\nThe Synod of the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] [[Canonization|canonized]] Dosoftei in July 2005, a fact that was proclaimed on October 14, 2005. His feast day is December 13.\n\n==Works==\n* ''Dosofteiu Mitropolitul Moldovei 1671\u20131686. Psaltirea in versuri publicata de pe manuscrisul original \u0219i de pe edi\u021biunea dela 1673 de Prof. I. Bianu. Edi\u021biunea Academie\u012d Rom\u00e2ne.'' Bucuresci 1887 ([https://books.google.com/books?id=OmRtAAAAIAAJ Google] [https:/